#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:21
msgid "Packaging Guide: defining a package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:23
msgid ""
"This packaging guide is intended for developers or administrators who want "
"to package software so that Spack can install it. It assumes that you have "
"at least some familiarity with Python, and that you've read the :ref:`basic "
"usage guide <basic-usage>`, especially the part about :ref:`specs <sec-"
"specs>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:26
msgid "There are two key parts of Spack:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:28
msgid "**Specs**: expressions for describing builds of software, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:29
msgid ""
"**Packages**: Python modules that describe how to build and test software "
"according to a spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:31
msgid ""
"Specs allow a user to describe a *particular* build in a way that a package "
"author can understand. Packages allow the packager to encapsulate the build "
"logic for different versions, compilers, options, platforms, and dependency "
"combinations in one place. Essentially, a package translates a spec into "
"build logic. It also allows the packager to write spec-specific tests of the "
"installed software."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:36
msgid ""
"Packages in Spack are written in pure Python, so you can do anything in "
"Spack that you can do in Python. Python was chosen as the implementation "
"language for two reasons. First, Python is ubiquitous in the scientific "
"software community. Second, it has many powerful features to help make "
"package writing easy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:45
msgid "Setting up for package development"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:47
msgid ""
"For developing new packages or working with existing ones, it's helpful to "
"have the ``spack/spack-packages`` repository in a convenient location like "
"your home directory, rather than the default ``~/.spack/package_repos/<hash>/"
"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:49
msgid ""
"If you plan to contribute changes back to Spack, we recommend creating a "
"fork of the `packages repository <https://github.com/spack/spack-"
"packages>`_. See `GitHub's fork documentation <https://docs.github.com/en/"
"pull-requests/collaborating-with-pull-requests/working-with-forks/fork-a-"
"repo>`_ for details. Once you have a fork, clone it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:53
msgid ""
"$ git clone --depth=100 git@github.com:YOUR-USERNAME/spack-packages.git ~/"
"spack-packages\n"
"$ cd ~/spack-packages\n"
"$ git remote add --track develop upstream git@github.com:spack/spack-"
"packages.git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:59
msgid "Then configure Spack to use your local repository:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:61
msgid "$ spack repo set --destination ~/spack-packages builtin"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:65
msgid ""
"Before starting work, it's useful to create a new branch in your local "
"repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:67
msgid "$ git checkout -b add-my-package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:71
msgid ""
"Lastly, verify that Spack is picking up the right repository by checking the "
"location of a known package, like ``zlib``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:73
msgid ""
"$ spack location --package-dir zlib\n"
"/home/your-username/spack-packages/repos/spack_repo/builtin/packages/zlib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:78
msgid ""
"With this setup, you can conveniently access the package files, and "
"contribute changes back to Spack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:81
msgid "Structure of a package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:83
msgid ""
"A Spack package is a Python module ``package.py`` stored in a package "
"repository. It contains a package class and sometimes a builder class that "
"define its metadata and build behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:86
msgid "The typical structure of a package is as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:88
msgid ""
"# spack_repo/builtin/packages/example/package.py\n"
"\n"
"# import of package / builder classes\n"
"from spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.cmake import CMakePackage\n"
"\n"
"# import Package API\n"
"from spack.package import *\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Example(CMakePackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"Example package\"\"\"  # package description\n"
"\n"
"    # Metadata and Directives\n"
"    homepage = \"https://example.com\"\n"
"    url = \"https://example.com/example/v2.4.0.tar.gz\"\n"
"\n"
"    maintainers(\"github_user1\", \"github_user2\")\n"
"\n"
"    license(\"UNKNOWN\", checked_by=\"github_user1\")\n"
"\n"
"    # version directives listed in order with the latest first\n"
"    version(\"2.4.0\", "
"sha256=\"845ccd79ed915fa2dedf3b2abde3fffe7f9f5673cc51be88e47e6432bd1408be\")\n"
"    version(\"2.3.0\", "
"sha256=\"cd3274e0abcbc2dfb678d87595e9d3ab1c6954d7921d57a88a23cf4981af46c9\")\n"
"\n"
"    # variant directives expose build options\n"
"    variant(\"feature\", default=False, description=\"Enable a specific "
"feature\")\n"
"    variant(\"codec\", default=False, description=\"Build the CODEC "
"executables\")\n"
"\n"
"    # dependency directives declare required software\n"
"    depends_on(\"cxx\", type=\"build\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"libfoo\", when=\"+feature\")\n"
"\n"
"    # Build Instructions\n"
"    def cmake_args(self):\n"
"        return [\n"
"            self.define_from_variant(\"BUILD_CODEC\", \"codec\"),\n"
"            self.define(\"EXAMPLE_OPTIMIZED\", False),\n"
"            self.define(\"BUILD_THIRDPARTY\", False),\n"
"        ]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:130
msgid ""
"The package class is named after the package, and can roughly be divided "
"into two parts:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:132
msgid ""
"**metadata and directives**: attributes and directives that describe the "
"package, such as its homepage, maintainers, license, variants, and "
"dependencies. This is the declarative part of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:134
msgid ""
"**build instructions**: methods that define how to build and install the "
"package, such as `cmake_args()`. This is the imperative part of the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:137
msgid ""
"In this part of the packaging guide we will cover the **metadata and "
"directives** in detail. In the :doc:`second part <packaging_guide_build>`, "
"we will cover the **build instructions**, including how to write custom "
"build logic for different build systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:141
msgid "Package Names and the Package Directory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:143
msgid ""
"Packages are referred to by their **package names**, whether it's on the "
"command line or in a package recipe. Package names can contain lowercase "
"letters, numbers, and dashes. Every package lives as a ``package.py`` file "
"in a **package directory** inside a :ref:`package repository "
"<repositories>`. Usually the package name coincides with the directory name "
"on the filesystem: the ``libelf`` package corresponds to the ``libelf/"
"package.py`` file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:150
msgid ""
"**Package name to directory mapping**. There is a one to one mapping between "
"package names and package directories. Usually the mapping is trivial: the "
"package name is the same as the directory name. However, there are a few "
"exceptions to this rule:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:155
msgid ""
"Hyphens in package names are replaced by underscores in directory names. For "
"example, the package name ``py-numpy`` maps to ``py_numpy/package.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:157
msgid ""
"Names starting with numbers get an underscore prefix. For example, the "
"package name ``7zip`` maps to ``_7zip/package.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:159
msgid ""
"Package names that are reserved keywords in Python are also prefixed with an "
"underscore. For example, the package name ``pass`` maps to ``_pass/package."
"py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:162
msgid ""
"This ensures that every package directory is a valid Python module name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:166
msgid "Package class names"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:168
msgid ""
"Spack loads ``package.py`` files dynamically, and it needs to find a special "
"class name in the file for the load to succeed. The **package class** is "
"formed by converting words separated by ``-`` in the package name to "
"CamelCase. If the package name starts with a number, we prefix the class "
"name with ``_``. Here are some examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:174
msgid "Package Name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:174
msgid "Class Name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:176
msgid "``foo-bar``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:176
msgid "``FooBar``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:177
msgid "``3proxy``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:177
msgid "``_3proxy``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:180
msgid ""
"In general, you won't have to remember this naming convention because :ref:"
"`cmd-spack-create` and :ref:`cmd-spack-edit` handle the details for you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:185
msgid "Creating and editing packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:187
msgid ""
"Spack has various commands that help you create and edit packages. Spack can "
"create the boilerplate for new packages and open them in your editor for you "
"to fill in. It can also help you edit existing packages, so you don't have "
"to navigate to the package directory manually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:195
msgid "Controlling the editor"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:197
msgid ""
"When Spack needs to open an editor for you (e.g., for commands like :ref:"
"`cmd-spack-create` or :ref:`cmd-spack-edit`), it looks at several "
"environment variables to figure out what to use. The order of precedence is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:200
msgid ""
"``SPACK_EDITOR``: highest precedence, in case you want something specific "
"for Spack;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:201
msgid ""
"``VISUAL``: standard environment variable for full-screen editors like "
"``vim`` or ``emacs``;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:202
msgid "``EDITOR``: older environment variable for your editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:204
msgid ""
"You can set any of these to the command you want to run, e.g., in ``bash`` "
"you might run one of these:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:206
msgid ""
"$ export VISUAL=vim\n"
"$ export EDITOR=\"emacs -nw\"\n"
"$ export SPACK_EDITOR=nano"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:212
msgid ""
"If Spack finds none of these variables set, it will look for ``vim``, "
"``vi``, ``emacs``, ``nano``, and ``notepad``, in that order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:217
msgid "Creating new packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:219
msgid ""
"To create a new package, Spack provides a command that generates a ``package."
"py`` file in an existing repository, with a boilerplate package template. "
"Here's an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:222
msgid "$ spack create https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:226
msgid ""
"Spack examines the tarball URL and tries to figure out the name of the "
"package to be created. If the name contains uppercase letters, these are "
"automatically converted to lowercase. If the name contains underscores or "
"periods, these are automatically converted to dashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:230
msgid ""
"Spack also searches for *additional* versions located in the same directory "
"on the website. Spack prompts you to tell you how many versions it found and "
"asks you how many you would like to download and checksum:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:233
msgid ""
"$ spack create https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2\n"
"==> This looks like a URL for gmp\n"
"==> Found 16 versions of gmp:\n"
"\n"
"  6.1.2   https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2\n"
"  6.1.1   https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.1.tar.bz2\n"
"  6.1.0   https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.0.tar.bz2\n"
"  ...\n"
"  5.0.0   https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-5.0.0.tar.bz2\n"
"\n"
"How many would you like to checksum? (default is 1, q to abort)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:247
msgid ""
"Spack will automatically download the number of tarballs you specify "
"(starting with the most recent) and checksum each of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:249
msgid ""
"You do not *have* to download all of the versions up front. You can always "
"choose to download just one tarball initially, and run :ref:`cmd-spack-"
"checksum` later if you need more versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:252
msgid ""
"Spack automatically creates a directory in the appropriate repository, "
"generates a boilerplate template for your package, and opens up the new "
"``package.py`` in your favorite ``$EDITOR`` (see :ref:`controlling-the-"
"editor` for details):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:254
msgid ""
"# Copyright Spack Project Developers. See COPYRIGHT file for details.\n"
"#\n"
"# SPDX-License-Identifier: (Apache-2.0 OR MIT)\n"
"\n"
"# "
"----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"# If you submit this package back to Spack as a pull request,\n"
"# please first remove this boilerplate and all FIXME comments.\n"
"#\n"
"# This is a template package file for Spack.  We've put \"FIXME\"\n"
"# next to all the things you'll want to change. Once you've handled\n"
"# them, you can save this file and test your package like this:\n"
"#\n"
"#     spack install gmp\n"
"#\n"
"# You can edit this file again by typing:\n"
"#\n"
"#     spack edit gmp\n"
"#\n"
"# See the Spack documentation for more information on packaging.\n"
"# "
"----------------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
"import spack_repo.builtin.build_systems.autotools\n"
"from spack.package import *\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Gmp(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"FIXME: Put a proper description of your package here.\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add a proper url for your package's homepage here.\n"
"    homepage = \"https://www.example.com\"\n"
"    url = \"https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2\"\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add a list of GitHub accounts to\n"
"    # notify when the package is updated.\n"
"    # maintainers(\"github_user1\", \"github_user2\")\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add the SPDX identifier of the project's license below.\n"
"    # See https://spdx.org/licenses/ for a list. Upon manually verifying\n"
"    # the license, set checked_by to your Github username.\n"
"    license(\"UNKNOWN\", checked_by=\"github_user1\")\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"6.2.1\", "
"sha256=\"eae9326beb4158c386e39a356818031bd28f3124cf915f8c5b1dc4c7a36b4d7c\")\n"
"\n"
"    # FIXME: Add dependencies if required.\n"
"    # depends_on(\"foo\")\n"
"\n"
"    def configure_args(self):\n"
"        # FIXME: Add arguments other than --prefix\n"
"        # FIXME: If not needed delete the function\n"
"        args = []\n"
"        return args"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:308
msgid ""
"The tedious stuff (creating the class, checksumming archives) has been done "
"for you. Spack correctly detected that ``gmp`` uses the ``autotools`` build "
"system, so it created a new ``Gmp`` package that subclasses the "
"``AutotoolsPackage`` base class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:311
msgid ""
"The default installation procedure for a package subclassing the "
"``AutotoolsPackage`` is to go through the typical process of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:313
msgid ""
"./configure --prefix=/path/to/installation/directory\n"
"make\n"
"make check\n"
"make install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:320
msgid ""
"For most Autotools packages, this is sufficient. If you need to add "
"additional arguments to the ``./configure`` call, add them via the "
"``configure_args`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:323
msgid ""
"In the generated package, the download ``url`` attribute is already set. All "
"the things you still need to change are marked with ``FIXME`` labels. You "
"can delete the commented instructions between the Spack license and the "
"first import statement after reading them. The remaining tasks to complete "
"are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:328
msgid "Add a description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:330
msgid ""
"Immediately inside the package class is a *docstring* in triple-quotes "
"(``\"\"\"``). It is used to generate the description shown when users run "
"``spack info``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:333
msgid "Change the ``homepage`` to a useful URL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:335
msgid ""
"The ``homepage`` is displayed when users run ``spack info`` so that they can "
"learn more about your package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:337
msgid "Add a comma-separated list of maintainers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:339
msgid ""
"Add a list of GitHub accounts of people who want to be notified any time the "
"package is modified. See :ref:`maintainers`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:342
msgid "Change the ``license`` to the correct license."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:344
msgid ""
"The ``license`` is displayed when users run ``spack info`` so that they can "
"learn more about your package. See :ref:`package_license`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:347
msgid "Add ``depends_on()`` calls for the package's dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:349
msgid ""
"``depends_on`` tells Spack that other packages need to be built and "
"installed before this one. See :ref:`dependencies`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:352
msgid "Get the installation working."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:354
msgid ""
"Your new package may require specific flags during ``configure``. These can "
"be added via ``configure_args``. If no arguments are needed at this time, "
"change the implementation to ``return []``. Specifics will differ depending "
"on the package and its build system. :ref:`installation_process` is covered "
"in detail later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:361
msgid "Further package creation options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:363
msgid ""
"If you do not have a tarball URL, you can still use ``spack create`` to "
"generate the boilerplate for a package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:365
msgid "$ spack create --name intel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:369
msgid ""
"This will create a simple ``intel`` package with an ``install()`` method "
"that you can craft to install your package. Likewise, you can force the "
"build system to be used with ``--template`` and, in case it's needed, you "
"can overwrite a package already in the repository with ``--force``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:372
msgid ""
"$ spack create --name gmp https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2\n"
"$ spack create --force --template autotools https://gmplib.org/download/gmp/"
"gmp-6.1.2.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:377
msgid ""
"A complete list of available build system templates can be found by running "
"``spack create --help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:382
msgid "Editing existing packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:384
msgid ""
"One of the easiest ways to learn how to write packages is to look at "
"existing ones. You can open an existing package in your editor using the "
"``spack edit`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:387
msgid "$ spack edit gmp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:391
msgid ""
"If you used ``spack create`` to create a package, you can get back to it "
"later with ``spack edit``. The ``spack edit`` command saves you the trouble "
"of figuring out the package location and navigating to it. If needed, you "
"can still find the package location using the ``spack location`` command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:395
msgid ""
"$ spack location --package-dir gmp\n"
"~/spack-packages/repos/spack_repo/builtin/packages/gmp/"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:400
msgid ""
"and with shell support enabled, you can also enter to the package directory:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:402
msgid "$ spack cd --package-dir gmp"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:406
msgid "If you want to edit multiple packages at once, you can run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:408
msgid "$ spack edit"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:412
msgid ""
"without specifying a package name, which will open the directory containing "
"all the packages in your editor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:414
msgid ""
"Finally, the commands ``spack location --repo`` and ``spack cd --repo`` help "
"you navigate to the root of the package repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:417
msgid "Source code and versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:419
msgid ""
"Spack packages are designed to be built from source code. Typically every "
"package version has a corresponding source code archive, which Spack "
"downloads and verifies before building the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:425
msgid "Versions and URLs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:427
msgid ""
"The most straightforward way to add new versions to your package is to add a "
"line like this in the package class:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:429
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    url = \"http://example.com/foo-8.2.1.tar.gz\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"8.2.1\", "
"sha256=\"85f477fdd6f8194ab6a0e7afd1cb34eae46c775278d5db9d7ebc9ddaf50c23b1\")\n"
"    version(\"8.2.0\", "
"sha256=\"427b2e244e73385515b8ad4f75358139d44a4c792d9b26ddffe2582835cedd8c\")\n"
"    version(\"8.1.2\", "
"sha256=\"67630a20f92ace137e68b67f13010487a03e4f036cdd328e199db85d24a434a4\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:441
msgid ""
"By convention, we list versions in descending order, from newest to oldest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:445
msgid ""
":ref:`Bundle packages  <bundlepackage>` do not have source code so there is "
"nothing to fetch. Consequently, their version directives consist solely of "
"the version name (e.g., ``version(\"202309\")``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:449
msgid ""
"Notice how you only have to specify the URL once, in the ``url`` field. "
"Spack is smart enough to extrapolate the URL for each version based on the "
"version number and download version ``8.2.0`` of the ``Foo`` package above "
"from ``http://example.com/foo-8.2.0.tar.gz``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:452
msgid ""
"If the URL is particularly complicated or changes based on the release, you "
"can override the default URL generation algorithm by defining your own :py:"
"meth:`~spack.package.PackageBase.url_for_version` function. For example, the "
"download URL for OpenMPI contains the ``major.minor`` version in one spot "
"and the ``major.minor.patch`` version in another:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:455
msgid ""
"https://www.open-mpi.org/software/ompi/v2.1/downloads/openmpi-2.1.1.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:459
msgid ""
"In order to handle this, you can define a ``url_for_version()`` function "
"like so:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:461
msgid ""
"    def url_for_version(self, version):\n"
"        url = \"https://download.open-mpi.org/release/open-mpi/v{0}/openmpi-"
"{1}.tar.bz2\"\n"
"        return url.format(version.up_to(2), version)\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:464
msgid ""
"With the use of this ``url_for_version()``, Spack knows to download OpenMPI "
"``2.1.1`` from"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:466
msgid ""
"http://www.open-mpi.org/software/ompi/v2.1/downloads/openmpi-2.1.1.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:470
msgid "but download OpenMPI ``1.10.7`` from"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:472
msgid ""
"http://www.open-mpi.org/software/ompi/v1.10/downloads/openmpi-1.10.7.tar.bz2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:476
msgid ""
"You'll notice that OpenMPI's ``url_for_version()`` function makes use of a "
"special ``Version`` function called ``up_to()``. When you call ``version."
"up_to(2)`` on a version like ``1.10.0``, it returns ``1.10``. ``version."
"up_to(1)`` would return ``1``. This can be very useful for packages that "
"place all ``X.Y.*`` versions in a single directory and then places all ``X.Y."
"Z`` versions in a sub-directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:481
msgid ""
"There are a few ``Version`` properties you should be aware of. We generally "
"prefer numeric versions to be separated by dots for uniformity, but not all "
"tarballs are named that way. For example, ``icu4c`` separates its major and "
"minor versions with underscores, like ``icu4c-57_1-src.tgz``. The value "
"``57_1`` can be obtained with the use of the ``version.underscored`` "
"property. There are other separator properties as well:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:488
msgid "Property"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:488
msgid "Result"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:490
msgid "version.dotted"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:490
msgid "1.2.3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:491
msgid "version.dashed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:491
msgid "1-2-3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:492
msgid "version.underscored"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:492
msgid "1_2_3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:493
msgid "version.joined"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:493
msgid "123"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:498
msgid ""
"Python properties don't need parentheses. ``version.dashed`` is correct. "
"``version.dashed()`` is incorrect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:502
msgid ""
"In addition, these version properties can be combined with ``up_to()``. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:505
msgid ""
">>> version = Version(\"1.2.3\")\n"
">>> version.up_to(2).dashed\n"
"Version(\"1-2\")\n"
">>> version.underscored.up_to(2)\n"
"Version(\"1_2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:514
msgid ""
"As you can see, order is not important. Just keep in mind that ``up_to()`` "
"and the other version properties return ``Version`` objects, not strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:517
msgid ""
"If a URL cannot be derived systematically, or there is a special URL for one "
"of its versions, you can add an explicit URL for a particular version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:519
msgid ""
"version(\n"
"    \"8.2.1\",\n"
"    sha256=\"91ee5e9f42ba3d34e414443b36a27b797a56a47aad6bb1e4c1769e69c77ce0ca\",\n"
"    url=\"http://example.com/foo-8.2.1-special-version.tar.gz\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:528
msgid ""
"When you supply a custom URL for a version, Spack uses that URL *verbatim* "
"and does not perform extrapolation. The order of precedence of these methods "
"is:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:531
msgid "package-level ``url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:532
msgid "``url_for_version()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:533
msgid "version-specific ``url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:535
msgid ""
"so if your package contains a ``url_for_version()``, it can be overridden by "
"a version-specific ``url``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:537
msgid ""
"If your package does not contain a package-level ``url`` or "
"``url_for_version()``, Spack can determine which URL to download from even "
"if only some of the versions specify their own ``url``. Spack will use the "
"nearest URL *before* the requested version. This is useful for packages that "
"have an easy to extrapolate URL, but keep changing their URL format every "
"few releases. With this method, you only need to specify the ``url`` when "
"the URL changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:545
msgid "Checksum verification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:547
msgid ""
"In the above example we see that each version is associated with a "
"``sha256`` checksum. Spack uses these checksums to verify that downloaded "
"source code has not been modified, corrupted or compromised. Therefore, "
"Spack requires that all URL downloads have a checksum, and refuses to "
"install packages when checksum verification fails."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:553
msgid ""
"While this requirement can be disabled for development with ``spack install "
"--no-checksum``, it is **not recommended**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:557
msgid ""
"**Trusted Downloads.** It is critical from a security and reproducibility "
"standpoint that Spack be able to verify the downloaded source. This is "
"accomplished using a hash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:561
msgid ""
"For URL downloads, Spack supports multiple cryptographic hash algorithms, "
"including ``sha256`` (recommended), ``sha384`` and ``sha512``. See :ref:"
"`version urls <versions-and-fetching>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:564
msgid ""
"For repository downloads, which we will cover in more detail later, this is "
"done by specifying a **full commit hash** (e.g., :ref:`git <git-commits>`, :"
"ref:`hg <hg-revisions>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:570
msgid "Automatically adding new versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:572
msgid ""
"The ``spack checksum`` command can be used to automate the process of adding "
"new versions to a package, assuming the package's download URLs follow a "
"consistent pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:575
msgid "``spack checksum``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:577
msgid "Using ``spack checksum`` is straightforward:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:579
msgid ""
"$ spack checksum libelf\n"
"==> Found 16 versions of libelf.\n"
"  0.8.13    http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.13.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.12    http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.12.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.11    http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.11.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.10    http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.10.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.9     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.9.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.8     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.8.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.7     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.7.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.6     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.6.tar.gz\n"
"  0.8.5     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.8.5.tar.gz\n"
"  ...\n"
"  0.5.2     http://www.mr511.de/software/libelf-0.5.2.tar.gz\n"
"\n"
"How many would you like to checksum? (default is 1, q to abort)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:597
msgid ""
"This does the same thing that ``spack create`` does, but it allows you to go "
"back and add new versions easily as you need them (e.g., as they're "
"released). It fetches the tarballs you ask for and prints out a list of "
"``version`` commands ready to copy/paste into your package file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:600
msgid ""
"==> Checksummed new versions of libelf:\n"
"    version(\"0.8.13\", "
"sha256=\"ec6ddbe4b1ac220244230b040fd6a5a102a96337603e703885848ff64cb582a5\")\n"
"    version(\"0.8.12\", "
"sha256=\"46db404a287b3d17210b4183cbc7055d7b8bbcb15957daeb51f2dc06002ca8a3\")\n"
"    version(\"0.8.11\", "
"sha256=\"e5be0f5d199ad11fbc74e59a8e120cc8b6fbcadaf1827c4e8e6a133ceaadbc4c\")\n"
"    version(\"0.8.10\", "
"sha256=\"f1708dd17a476a7abaf6c395723e0745ba8f6b196115513b6d8922d4b5bfbab4\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:610
msgid ""
"``spack checksum`` assumes that Spack can extrapolate new URLs from an "
"existing URL in the package, and that Spack can find similar URLs on a "
"webpage. If that's not possible, e.g., if the package's developers don't "
"name their source archive consistently, you'll need to manually add "
"``version`` calls yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:613
msgid ""
"By default, Spack will search for new versions by scraping the parent URL "
"component of the source archive you gave it in the ``url`` attribute. So, if "
"the sources are at ``http://example.com/downloads/foo-1.0.tar.gz``, Spack "
"computes a *list URL* from it ``http://example.com/downloads/``, and scans "
"that for links to other versions of the package. If you need to search "
"another path for download links, you can supply some extra attributes that "
"control how your package finds new versions. See the documentation on :ref:"
"`attribute_list_url` and :ref:`attribute_list_depth`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:621
msgid "Git Version Provenance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:623
msgid ""
"Checksummed assets are preferred but there are a few notable exceptions such "
"as git branches and tags i.e ``pkg@develop``. These versions do not "
"naturally have source provenance because they refer to a range of commits "
"(branches) or can be changed outside the spack packaging infrastructure "
"(tags). Without source provenance we cannot have full provenance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:627
msgid ""
"Spack has a reserved variant to allow users to complete provenance for these "
"cases: ``pkg@develop commit=<SHA>``. The ``commit`` variant must be supplied "
"using the full 40 character commit SHA. Using a partial commit SHA or "
"assigning the ``commit`` variant to a version that is not using a branch or "
"tag reference will lead to an error during concretization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:631
msgid ""
"Spack will attempt to establish git version provenance by looking up commit "
"SHA's for branch and tag based versions during concretization. There are 3 "
"sources that it uses. In order, they are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:635
msgid ""
"The local cached downloads (already cached source code for the version "
"needing provenance)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:636
msgid "Source mirrors (compressed archives of the source code)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:637
msgid "The git url provided in the package definition"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:639
msgid ""
"If Spack is unable to determine what the commit should be during "
"concretization a warning will be issued. Users may also specify which commit "
"SHA they want with the spec since it is simply a variant. In this case, or "
"in the case of develop specs (see :ref:`cmd-spack-develop`), Spack will skip "
"attempts to assign the commit SHA automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:645
msgid ""
"Users wanting to track the latest commits from the internet should utilize "
"``spack clean --downloads`` prior to concretization to clean out cached "
"downloads that will short-circuit internet queries. Disabling source mirrors "
"or ensuring they don't contain branch/tag based versions will also be "
"necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:648
msgid ""
"Above all else, the most robust way to ensure binaries have their desired "
"commits is to provide the SHAs via user-specs or config i.e. "
"``commit=<SHA>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:655
msgid "``list_url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:657
msgid ""
"This optional attribute can be set to tell Spack where to scan for links to "
"other versions of the package. For example, the following package has a "
"``list_url`` attribute that points to a page listing all available versions "
"of the package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:660
msgid ""
"class Example(Package):\n"
"    homepage = \"http://www.example.com\"\n"
"    url = \"http://www.example.com/libexample-1.2.3.tar.gz\"\n"
"    list_url = \"http://www.example.com/downloads/all-versions.html\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:671
msgid "``list_depth``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:673
msgid ""
"Many packages have a listing of available versions on a single webpage, but "
"not all do. For example, ``mpich`` has a tarball URL that looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:676
msgid ""
"url = \"http://www.mpich.org/static/downloads/3.0.4/mpich-3.0.4.tar.gz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:680
msgid ""
"But its downloads are a few clicks away from ``http://www.mpich.org/static/"
"downloads/``. So, we need to add a ``list_url`` *and* a ``list_depth`` "
"attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:683
msgid ""
"class Mpich(Package):\n"
"    homepage = \"http://www.mpich.org\"\n"
"    url = \"http://www.mpich.org/static/downloads/3.0.4/mpich-3.0.4.tar."
"gz\"\n"
"    list_url = \"http://www.mpich.org/static/downloads/\"\n"
"    list_depth = 1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:692
msgid ""
"By default, Spack only looks at the top-level page available at "
"``list_url``. ``list_depth = 1`` tells it to follow up to 1 level of links "
"from the top-level page. Note that here, this implies 1 level of "
"subdirectories, as the ``mpich`` website is structured much like a "
"filesystem. But ``list_depth`` really refers to link depth when spidering "
"the page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:700
msgid "Mirrors of the main URL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:702
msgid ""
"Spack supports listing mirrors of the main URL in a package by defining the "
"``urls`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:704
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    urls = [\"http://example.com/foo-1.0.tar.gz\", \"http://mirror.com/"
"foo-1.0.tar.gz\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:710
msgid ""
"instead of just a single ``url``. This attribute is a list of possible URLs "
"that will be tried in order when fetching packages. Notice that either one "
"of ``url`` or ``urls`` can be present in a package, but not both at the same "
"time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:714
msgid ""
"A well-known case of packages that can be fetched from multiple mirrors is "
"that of GNU. For that, Spack goes a step further and defines a mixin class "
"that takes care of all of the plumbing and requires packagers to just define "
"a proper ``gnu_mirror_path`` attribute:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:717
msgid ""
"\n"
"from spack.package import *\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class Autoconf(AutotoolsPackage, GNUMirrorPackage):\n"
"    \"\"\"Autoconf -- system configuration part of autotools\"\"\"\n"
"\n"
"    homepage = \"https://www.gnu.org/software/autoconf/\"\n"
"    gnu_mirror_path = \"autoconf/autoconf-2.69.tar.gz\"\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:724
msgid "Preferring versions over others"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:726
msgid ""
"When users install a package without constraining the versions, Spack will "
"typically pick the latest version available. Usually this is the desired "
"behavior, but as a packager you may know that the latest version is not "
"mature enough or has known issues that make it unsuitable for production "
"use. In this case, you can mark an older version as preferred using the "
"``preferred=True`` argument in the ``version`` directive, so that Spack will "
"default to the latest *preferred* version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:730
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    version(\"2.0.0\", sha256=\"...\")\n"
"    version(\"1.2.3\", sha256=\"...\", preferred=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:736
msgid ""
"See the section on :ref:`version ordering <version-comparison>` for more "
"details and exceptions on how the latest version is computed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:742
msgid "Deprecating old versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:744
msgid "There are many reasons to remove old versions of software:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:746
msgid "Security vulnerabilities (most serious reason)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:747
msgid "No longer available for download (right to be forgotten)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:748
msgid "Maintainer/developer inability/unwillingness to support old versions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:749
msgid "Changing build systems that increase package complexity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:750
msgid ""
"Changing dependencies/patches/resources/flags that increase package "
"complexity"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:751
msgid "Package or version rename"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:753
msgid ""
"At the same time, there are many reasons to keep old versions of software:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:755
msgid "Reproducibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:756
msgid ""
"Requirements for older packages (e.g., some packages still rely on Qt 3)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:758
msgid ""
"In general, you should not remove old versions from a ``package.py`` "
"directly. Instead, you should first deprecate them using the following "
"syntax:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:761
msgid "version(\"1.2.3\", sha256=\"...\", deprecated=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:766
msgid ""
"This has two effects. First, ``spack info`` will no longer advertise that "
"version. Second, commands like ``spack install`` that fetch the package will "
"require user approval:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:770
msgid ""
"$ spack install openssl@1.0.1e\n"
"==> Warning: openssl@1.0.1e is deprecated and may be removed in a future "
"Spack release.\n"
"==>   Fetch anyway? [y/N]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:777
msgid "If you use ``spack install --deprecated``, this check can be skipped."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:779
msgid ""
"This also applies to package recipes that are renamed or removed. You should "
"first deprecate all versions before removing a package. If you need to "
"rename it, you can deprecate the old package and create a new package at the "
"same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:783
msgid ""
"Version deprecations should always last at least one release cycle of the "
"builtin package repository before the version is completely removed. No "
"version should be removed without such a deprecation process. This gives "
"users a chance to complain about the deprecation in case the old version is "
"needed for some application. If you require a deprecated version of a "
"package, simply submit a PR to remove ``deprecated=True`` from the package. "
"However, you may be asked to help maintain this version of the package if "
"the current maintainers are unwilling to support this older version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:793
msgid "Version ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:795
msgid ""
"Without :ref:`version constraints <version_constraints>`, :ref:`preferences "
"<preferred_versions>` and :ref:`deprecations <deprecate>`, Spack will always "
"pick *the latest* version as defined in the package. What latest means is "
"determined by the version comparison rules defined in Spack, *not* the order "
"in which versions are listed in the package file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:798
msgid ""
"Spack imposes a generic total ordering on the set of versions, independently "
"from the package they are associated with."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:800
msgid ""
"Most Spack versions are numeric, a tuple of integers; for example, ``0.1``, "
"``6.96``, or ``1.2.3.1``. In this very basic case, version comparison is "
"lexicographical on the numeric components: ``1.2 < 1.2.1 < 1.2.2 < 1.10``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:803
msgid ""
"Other separators for components are also possible, for example ``2025-03-01 "
"< 2025-06``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:805
msgid ""
"Spack can also support string components such as ``1.1.1a`` and ``1.y.0``. "
"String components are considered less than numeric components, so ``1.y.0 < "
"1.0``. This is for consistency with `RPM <https://bugzilla.redhat.com/"
"show_bug.cgi?id=50977>`_. String components do not have to be separated by "
"dots or any other delimiter. So, the contrived version ``1y0`` is identical "
"to ``1.y.0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:811
msgid ""
"Pre-release suffixes also contain string parts, but they are handled in a "
"special way. For example ``1.2.3alpha1`` is parsed as a pre-release of the "
"version ``1.2.3``. This allows Spack to order it before the actual release: "
"``1.2.3alpha1 < 1.2.3``. Spack supports alpha, beta and release candidate "
"suffixes: ``1.2alpha1 < 1.2beta1 < 1.2rc1 < 1.2``. Any suffix not recognized "
"as a pre-release is treated as an ordinary string component, so ``1.2 < 1.2-"
"mysuffix``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:817
msgid ""
"Finally, there are a few special string components that are considered "
"\"infinity versions\". They include ``develop``, ``main``, ``master``, "
"``head``, ``trunk``, and ``stable``, in descending order. For example: ``1.2 "
"< develop``. These are useful for specifying the most recent development "
"version of a package (often a moving target like a git branch), without "
"assigning a specific version number. Infinity versions are not automatically "
"used when determining the latest version of a package unless explicitly "
"required by another package or user."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:823
msgid ""
"More formally, the order on versions is defined as follows. A version string "
"is split into a list of components based on delimiters such as ``.``, ``-``, "
"``_``, and string boundaries. The components are split into the **release** "
"and a possible **pre-release** (if the last component is numeric and the "
"second to last is a string ``alpha``, ``beta`` or ``rc``). The release "
"components are ordered lexicographically, with comparison between different "
"types of components as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:828
msgid ""
"The following special strings are considered larger than any other numeric "
"or non-numeric version component, and satisfy the following order between "
"themselves: ``develop > main > master > head > trunk > stable``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:830
msgid ""
"Numbers are ordered numerically, are less than special strings, and larger "
"than other non-numeric components."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:832
msgid ""
"All other non-numeric components are less than numeric components, and are "
"ordered alphabetically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:834
msgid ""
"Finally, if the release components are equal, the pre-release components are "
"used to break the tie."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:836
msgid "The logic behind this sort order is two-fold:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:838
msgid ""
"Non-numeric versions are usually used for special cases while developing or "
"debugging a piece of software. Keeping most of them less than numeric "
"versions ensures that Spack chooses numeric versions by default whenever "
"possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:841
msgid ""
"The most-recent development version of a package will usually be newer than "
"any released numeric versions. This allows the ``@develop`` version to "
"satisfy dependencies like ``depends_on(abc, when=\"@x.y.z:\")``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:848
msgid "Fetching from code repositories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:850
msgid ""
"For some packages, source code is provided in a Version Control System (VCS) "
"repository rather than in a tarball. Spack can fetch packages from VCS "
"repositories. Currently, Spack supports fetching with :ref:`Git <git-"
"fetch>`, :ref:`Mercurial (hg) <hg-fetch>`, :ref:`Subversion (svn) <svn-"
"fetch>`, and :ref:`CVS (cvs) <cvs-fetch>`. In all cases, the destination is "
"the standard stage source path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:855
msgid ""
"To fetch a package from a source repository, Spack needs to know which VCS "
"to use and where to download from. Much like with ``url``, package authors "
"can specify a class-level ``git``, ``hg``, ``svn``, or ``cvs`` attribute "
"containing the correct download location."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:858
msgid ""
"Many packages developed with Git have both a Git repository as well as "
"release tarballs available for download. Packages can define both a class-"
"level tarball URL and VCS. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:862
msgid ""
"class Trilinos(CMakePackage):\n"
"\n"
"    homepage = \"https://trilinos.org/\"\n"
"    url = \"https://github.com/trilinos/Trilinos/archive/trilinos-"
"release-12-12-1.tar.gz\"\n"
"    git = \"https://github.com/trilinos/Trilinos.git\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"develop\", branch=\"develop\")\n"
"    version(\"master\", branch=\"master\")\n"
"    version(\"12.12.1\", "
"sha256=\"87428fc522803d31065e7bce3cf03fe475096631e5e07bbd7a0fde60c4cf25c7\")\n"
"    version(\"12.10.1\", "
"sha256=\"0263829989b6fd954f72baaf2fc64bc2e2f01d692d4de72986ea808f6e99813f\")\n"
"    version(\"12.8.1\", "
"sha256=\"a3a5e715f0cc574a73c3f9bebb6bc24f32ffd5b67b387244c2c909da779a1478\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:876
msgid ""
"If a package contains both a ``url`` and ``git`` class-level attribute, "
"Spack decides which to use based on the arguments to the ``version()`` "
"directive. Versions containing a specific branch, tag, commit or revision "
"are assumed to be for VCS download methods, while versions containing a "
"checksum are assumed to be for URL download methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:879
msgid ""
"Like ``url``, if a specific version downloads from a different repository "
"than the default repo, it can be overridden with a version-specific argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:883
msgid ""
"In order to reduce ambiguity, each package can only have a single VCS top-"
"level attribute in addition to ``url``. In the rare case that a package uses "
"multiple VCS, a fetch strategy can be specified for each version. For "
"example, the ``rockstar`` package contains:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:887
msgid ""
"class Rockstar(MakefilePackage):\n"
"\n"
"    homepage = \"https://bitbucket.org/gfcstanford/rockstar\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"develop\", git=\"https://bitbucket.org/gfcstanford/rockstar."
"git\")\n"
"    version(\"yt\", hg=\"https://bitbucket.org/MatthewTurk/rockstar\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:900
msgid "Git"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:902
msgid ""
"Git fetching supports the following parameters to the ``version`` directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:904
msgid ""
"``git``: URL of the git repository, if different than the class-level "
"``git``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:905
msgid "``branch``: Name of a :ref:`branch <git-branches>` to fetch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:906
msgid "``tag``: Name of a :ref:`tag <git-tags>` to fetch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:907
msgid ""
"``commit``: SHA hash (or prefix) of a :ref:`commit <git-commits>` to fetch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:908
msgid ""
"``submodules``: Also fetch :ref:`submodules <git-submodules>` recursively "
"when checking out this repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:909
msgid ""
"``submodules_delete``: A list of submodules to forcibly delete from the "
"repository after fetching. Useful if a version in the repository has "
"submodules that have disappeared/are no longer accessible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:911
msgid ""
"``get_full_repo``: Ensure the full git history is checked out with all "
"remote branch information. Normally (``get_full_repo=False``, the default), "
"the git option ``--depth 1`` will be used if the version of git and the "
"specified transport protocol support it, and ``--single-branch`` will be "
"used if the version of git supports it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:913
msgid ""
"``git_sparse_paths``: Only clone the provided :ref:`relative paths <git-"
"sparse-checkout>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:915
msgid ""
"The destination directory for the clone is the standard stage source path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:919
msgid ""
"``tag`` and ``branch`` should not be combined in the version parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:921
msgid ""
"We strongly recommend that all ``tag`` entries be paired with ``commit``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:926
msgid ""
"**Trusted Downloads.** It is critical from a security and reproducibility "
"standpoint that Spack be able to verify the downloaded source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:929
msgid ""
"Providing the full ``commit`` SHA hash allows for Spack to preserve "
"provenance for all binaries since git commits are guaranteed to be unique "
"points in the git history. Whereas, the mutable nature of branches and tags "
"cannot provide such a guarantee."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:932
msgid ""
"A git download *is trusted* only if the full commit SHA is specified. "
"Therefore, it is *the* recommended way to securely download from a Git "
"repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:938
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1147
msgid "Default branch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:939
msgid ""
"A version with only a name results in fetching a repository's default branch:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:941
msgid ""
"class Example(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    git = \"https://github.com/example-project/example.git\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"develop\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:949
msgid ""
"Aside from use of HTTPS, there is no way to verify that the repository has "
"not been compromised. Furthermore, the commit you get when you install the "
"package likely won't be the same commit that was used when the package was "
"first written. There is also the risk that the default branch may change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:955
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:997
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1162
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1221
msgid "This download method is **untrusted**, and is **not recommended**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:957
msgid ""
"It is better to specify a branch name (see :ref:`below <git-branches>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:962
msgid "Branches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:963
msgid ""
"To fetch a particular branch, use the ``branch`` parameter, preferably with "
"the same name as the version. For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:966
msgid ""
"version(\"main\", branch=\"main\")\n"
"version(\"experimental\", branch=\"experimental\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:971
msgid ""
"Branches are moving targets, which means the commit you get when you install "
"the package likely won't be the one used when the package was first written."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:975
msgid ""
"Common branch names are special in terms of how Spack determines the latest "
"version of a package. See \"infinity versions\" in :ref:`version ordering "
"<version-comparison>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:980
msgid ""
"This download method is **untrusted**, and is **not recommended** for "
"production installations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:985
msgid "Tags"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:986
msgid "To fetch from a particular tag, use ``tag`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:988
msgid "version(\"1.0.1\", tag=\"v1.0.1\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:992
msgid ""
"While tags are generally more stable than branches, Git allows tags to be "
"moved. Many developers use tags to denote rolling releases, and may move the "
"tag when a bug is fixed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:999
msgid ""
"If you must use a ``tag``, it is recommended to combine it with the "
"``commit`` option (see :ref:`below <git-commits>`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1004
msgid "Commits"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1005
msgid "To fetch a particular commit, use the ``commit`` argument:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1007
msgid ""
"version(\"2014-10-08\", "
"commit=\"1e6ef73d93a28240f954513bc4c2ed46178fa32b\")\n"
"version(\"1.0.4\", tag=\"v1.0.4\", "
"commit=\"420136f6f1f26050d95138e27cf8bc905bc5e7f52\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1012
msgid ""
"It may be useful to provide a saner version for commits like this, e.g., you "
"might use the date as the version, as done in the first example above. Or, "
"if you know the commit at which a release was cut, you can use the release "
"version. It is up to the package author to decide which of these options "
"makes the most sense."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1018
msgid ""
"A git download is *trusted only if* the **full commit sha** is specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1023
msgid ""
"**Avoid using the commit hash as the version.** It is not recommended to use "
"the commit hash as the version itself, since it won't sort properly for :ref:"
"`version ordering <version-comparison>` purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1029
msgid "Submodules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1030
msgid ""
"You can supply ``submodules=True`` to cause Spack to fetch submodules "
"recursively along with the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1032
msgid ""
"version(\"1.1.0\", commit=\"907d5f40d653a73955387067799913397807adf3\", "
"submodules=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1036
msgid ""
"If a package needs more fine-grained control over submodules, define "
"``submodules`` to be a callable function that takes the package instance as "
"its only argument. The function needs to return a list of submodules to be "
"fetched."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1039
msgid ""
"def submodules(package):\n"
"    submodules = []\n"
"    if \"+variant-1\" in package.spec:\n"
"        submodules.append(\"submodule_for_variant_1\")\n"
"    if \"+variant-2\" in package.spec:\n"
"        submodules.append(\"submodule_for_variant_2\")\n"
"    return submodules\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    version(\"1.1.0\", commit=\"907d5f40d653a73955387067799913397807adf3\", "
"submodules=submodules)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1053
msgid ""
"For more information about git submodules see the man page of git: ``man git-"
"submodule``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1058
msgid "Sparse-Checkout"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1059
msgid ""
"If you only want to clone a subset of the contents of a git repository, you "
"can supply ``git_sparse_paths`` at the package or version level to utilize "
"git's sparse-checkout feature. The paths can be specified through an "
"attribute, property or callable function. This option is useful for large "
"repositories containing separate features that can be built independently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1065
msgid ""
"This leverages a newer feature in git that requires version ``2.25.0`` or "
"greater."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1067
msgid ""
"If ``git_sparse_paths`` is supplied to a git version that is too old then a "
"warning will be issued before standard cloning operations are performed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1071
msgid ""
"Paths to directories result in the cloning of *all* of their contents, "
"including the contents of their subdirectories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1073
msgid ""
"The ``git_sparse_paths`` attribute needs to provide a list of relative paths "
"within the repository. If using a property -- a function decorated with "
"``@property`` -- or an argument that is a callable function, the function "
"needs to return a list of paths."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1076
msgid "For example, using the attribute approach:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1078
msgid ""
"class MyPackage(package):\n"
"    # using an attribute\n"
"    git_sparse_paths = [\"doe\", \"rae\"]\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"1.0.0\")\n"
"    version(\"1.1.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1087
msgid ""
"results in the files from the top level directory of the repository and the "
"contents of the ``doe`` and ``rae`` relative paths within the repository to "
"be cloned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1089
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can provide the paths to the version directive argument "
"using a callable function whose return value is a list for paths. For "
"example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1092
msgid ""
"def sparse_path_function(package):\n"
"    paths = [\"doe\", \"rae\", \"me/file.cpp\"]\n"
"    if package.spec.version > Version(\"1.2.0\"):\n"
"        paths.extend([\"fae\"])\n"
"    return paths\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"class MyPackage(Package):\n"
"    version(\"1.1.5\", git_sparse_paths=sparse_path_function)\n"
"    version(\"1.2.0\", git_sparse_paths=sparse_path_function)\n"
"    version(\"1.2.5\", git_sparse_paths=sparse_path_function)\n"
"    version(\"1.1.5\", git_sparse_paths=sparse_path_function)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1107
msgid ""
"results in the cloning of the files from the top level directory of the "
"repository, the contents of the ``doe`` and ``rae`` relative paths, *and* "
"the ``me/file.cpp`` file. If the package version is greater than ``1.2.0`` "
"then the contents of the ``fae`` relative path will also be cloned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1112
msgid ""
"The version directives in the examples above are simplified to emphasize use "
"of this feature. Trusted downloads require a hash, such as a :ref:`sha256 "
"<github-fetch>` or :ref:`commit <git-commits>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1119
msgid "GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1121
msgid ""
"If a project is hosted on GitHub, *any* valid Git branch, tag, or hash may "
"be downloaded as a tarball. This is accomplished simply by constructing an "
"appropriate URL. Spack can checksum any package downloaded this way, thereby "
"producing a trusted download. For example, the following downloads a "
"particular hash, and then applies a checksum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1126
msgid ""
"version(\n"
"    \"1.9.5.1.1\",\n"
"    sha256=\"8d74beec1be996322ad76813bafb92d40839895d6dd7ee808b17ca201eac98be\",\n"
"    url=\"https://www.github.com/jswhit/pyproj/"
"tarball/0be612cc9f972e38b50a90c946a9b353e2ab140f\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1134
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you could provide the GitHub ``url`` for one version as a "
"property and Spack will extrapolate the URL for other versions as described "
"in :ref:`Versions and URLs <versions-and-fetching>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1140
msgid "Mercurial"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1142
msgid ""
"Fetching with Mercurial works much like :ref:`Git <git-fetch>`, but you use "
"the ``hg`` parameter. The destination directory is still the standard stage "
"source path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1148
msgid "Add the ``hg`` attribute with no ``revision`` passed to ``version``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1150
msgid ""
"class Example(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    hg = \"https://bitbucket.org/example-project/example\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"develop\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1158
msgid ""
"As with Git's default fetching strategy, there is no way to verify the "
"integrity of the download."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1167
msgid "Revisions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1168
msgid "To fetch a particular revision, use the ``revision`` parameter:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1170
msgid "version(\"1.0\", revision=\"v1.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1174
msgid ""
"Unlike ``git``, which has special parameters for different types of "
"revisions, you can use ``revision`` for branches, tags, and **commits** when "
"you fetch with Mercurial."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1178
msgid ""
"Like Git, fetching specific branches or tags is an **untrusted** download "
"method, and is **not recommended**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1180
msgid ""
"The recommended fetch strategy is to specify a particular commit hash as the "
"revision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1186
msgid "Subversion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1188
msgid ""
"To fetch with subversion, use the ``svn`` and ``revision`` parameters. The "
"destination directory will be the standard stage source path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1191
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1241
msgid "Fetching the head"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1192
msgid "Simply add an ``svn`` parameter to the package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1194
msgid ""
"class Example(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    svn = \"https://outreach.scidac.gov/svn/example/trunk\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"develop\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1204
msgid ""
"This download method is **untrusted**, and is **not recommended** for the "
"same reasons as mentioned above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1209
msgid "Fetching a revision"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1210
msgid ""
"To fetch a particular revision, add a ``revision`` argument to the version "
"directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1212
msgid "version(\"develop\", revision=128)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1216
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, Subversion has no commit hashing scheme like Git and "
"Mercurial do, so there is no way to guarantee that the download you get is "
"the same as the download used when the package was created. Use at your own "
"risk."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1224
msgid ""
"Subversion branches are handled as part of the directory structure, so you "
"can check out a branch or tag by changing the URL. If you want to package "
"multiple branches, simply add a ``svn`` argument to each version directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1231
msgid "CVS"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1233
msgid ""
"CVS (Concurrent Versions System) is an old centralized version control "
"system. It is a predecessor of Subversion."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1236
msgid ""
"To fetch with CVS, use the ``cvs``, branch, and ``date`` parameters. The "
"destination directory will be the standard stage source path."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1242
msgid "Simply add a ``cvs`` parameter to the package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1244
msgid ""
"class Example(Package):\n"
"\n"
"    cvs = \":pserver:outreach.scidac.gov/cvsroot%module=modulename\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"1.1.2.4\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1252
msgid ""
"CVS repository locations are described using an older syntax that is "
"different from today's ubiquitous URL syntax. ``:pserver:`` denotes the "
"transport method. CVS servers can host multiple repositories (called "
"\"modules\") at the same location, and one needs to specify both the server "
"location and the module name to access. Spack combines both into one string "
"using the ``%module=modulename`` suffix shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1259
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1277
msgid "This download method is **untrusted**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1264
msgid "Fetching a date"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1265
msgid ""
"Versions in CVS are commonly specified by date. To fetch a particular branch "
"or date, add a ``branch`` and/or ``date`` argument to the version directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1268
msgid "version(\"2021.4.22\", branch=\"branchname\", date=\"2021-04-22\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1272
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, CVS does not identify repository-wide commits via a revision "
"or hash like Subversion, Git, or Mercurial do. This makes it impossible to "
"specify an exact commit to check out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1280
msgid ""
"CVS has more features, but since CVS is rarely used these days, Spack does "
"not support all of them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1283
msgid "Sources that are not archives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1285
msgid ""
"Spack normally expands archives (e.g., ``*.tar.gz`` and ``*.zip``) "
"automatically into a standard stage source directory (``self.stage."
"source_path``) after downloading them. If you want to skip this step (e.g., "
"for self-extracting executables and other custom archive types), you can add "
"``expand=False`` to a ``version`` directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1288
msgid ""
"version(\n"
"    \"8.2.1\",\n"
"    sha256=\"a2bbdb2de53523b8099b37013f251546f3d65dbe7a0774fa41af0a4176992fd4\",\n"
"    url=\"http://example.com/foo-8.2.1-special-version.sh\",\n"
"    expand=False,\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1297
msgid ""
"When ``expand`` is set to ``False``, Spack sets the current working "
"directory to the directory containing the downloaded archive before it calls "
"your ``install`` method. Within ``install``, the path to the downloaded "
"archive is available as ``self.stage.archive_file``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1300
msgid ""
"Here is an example snippet for packages distributed as self-extracting "
"archives. The example sets permissions on the downloaded file to make it "
"executable, then runs it with some arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1303
msgid ""
"def install(self, spec, prefix):\n"
"    set_executable(self.stage.archive_file)\n"
"    installer = Executable(self.stage.archive_file)\n"
"    installer(\"--prefix=%s\" % prefix, \"arg1\", \"arg2\", \"etc.\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1312
msgid "Extra Resources"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1314
msgid ""
"Some packages (most notably compilers) provide optional features if "
"additional resources are expanded within their source tree before building. "
"In Spack it is possible to describe such a need with the ``resource`` "
"directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1317
msgid ""
"resource(\n"
"    name=\"cargo\",\n"
"    git=\"https://github.com/rust-lang/cargo.git\",\n"
"    tag=\"0.10.0\",\n"
"    destination=\"cargo\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1326
msgid ""
"The arguments are similar to those of the ``versions`` directive. The "
"keyword ``destination`` is relative to the source root of the package and "
"should point to where the resource is to be expanded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1330
msgid "Download caching"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1332
msgid ""
"Spack maintains a cache (described :ref:`here <caching>`) which saves files "
"retrieved during package installations to avoid re-downloading in the case "
"that a package is installed with a different specification (but the same "
"version) or reinstalled on account of a change in the hashing scheme. In "
"rare cases, it may be necessary to avoid caching for a particular version by "
"adding ``no_cache=True`` as an option to the ``version()`` directive. "
"Example situations would be a \"snapshot\"-like Version Control System (VCS) "
"tag, a VCS branch such as ``v6-16-00-patches``, or a URL specifying a "
"regularly updated snapshot tarball."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1340
msgid "Specifying version constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1342
msgid ""
"Many Spack directives allow limiting versions to support features such as :"
"ref:`backward and forward compatibility <version_compatibility>`. These "
"constraints on :ref:`package specs <sec-specs>` are defined using the "
"``@<specifier>`` syntax. (See :ref:`version-specifier` for more information.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1346
msgid "For example, the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1348
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"foo\")\n"
"depends_on(\"python@3\")\n"
"\n"
"conflicts(\"^foo@1.2.3:\", when=\"@:4.5\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1355
msgid ""
"illustrates, in order, three of four forms of version range constraints: "
"implicit, lower bound and upper bound. The fourth form provides lower *and* "
"upper bounds on the version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1358
msgid ""
"In this example, the implicit range is used to indicate that the package :"
"ref:`depends on <dependencies>` *any* ``python`` *with* ``3`` *as the major "
"version number* (e.g., ``3.13.5``). The other two range constraints are "
"shown in the :ref:`conflict <packaging_conflicts>` with the dependency "
"package ``foo``. The conflict with ``foo`` *at version* ``1.2.3`` *or newer* "
"is **triggered** for builds of the package at *any version up to and "
"including* ``4.5``. For an example of the fourth form, suppose the "
"dependency in this example had been ``python@3.6:3``. In this case, the "
"package would depend on *any version of* ``python`` *from* ``3.6`` *on so "
"long as the major version number is* ``3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1364
msgid ""
"While you can constrain the spec to a single version -- using the "
"``@=<version>`` form of ``specifier`` -- **ranges are preferred** even if "
"they would only match a single version currently defined in the package. "
"Using ranges helps avoid overly constrained dependencies, patches, and "
"conflicts. They also come in handy when, for example, users define versions "
"in :ref:`packages-config` that include custom suffixes. For example, if the "
"package defines the version ``1.2.3``, we know from :ref:`version-"
"comparison`, that a user-defined version ``1.2.3-custom`` will satisfy the "
"version constraint ``@1.2.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1371
msgid ""
"Specific ``@=`` versions should only be used in **exceptional cases**, such "
"as when the package has a versioning scheme that omits the zero in the first "
"patch release. For example, suppose a package defines versions: ``3.1``, "
"``3.1.1`` and ``3.1.2``. Then the specifier ``@=3.1`` is the correct way to "
"select only ``3.1``, whereas ``@3.1`` would be satisfied by all three "
"versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1379
msgid "Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1381
msgid ""
"Many software packages can be configured to enable optional features, which "
"often come at the expense of additional dependencies or longer build times. "
"To be flexible enough and support a wide variety of use cases, Spack allows "
"you to expose to the end-user the ability to choose which features should be "
"activated in a package at the time it is installed. The mechanism to be "
"employed is the :py:func:`~spack.package.variant` directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1386
msgid "Boolean variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1388
msgid ""
"In their simplest form, variants are boolean options specified at the "
"package level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1390
msgid ""
"class Hdf5(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"shared\", default=True, description=\"Builds a shared version "
"of the library\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1396
msgid "with a default value and a description of their meaning in the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1398
msgid ""
"With this variant defined, users can now run ``spack install hdf5 +shared`` "
"and ``spack install hdf5 ~shared`` to enable or disable the ``shared`` "
"feature, respectively. See also the :ref:`basic-variants` for the spec "
"syntax of variants."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1401
msgid ""
"Of course, merely defining a variant in a package does not automatically "
"enable or disable any features in the build system. As a packager, you are "
"responsible for translating variants to build system flags or environment "
"variables, to influence the build process. We will see this in action in the "
"next part of the packaging guide, where we talk about :ref:`configuring the "
"build with spec objects <spec-objects>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1405
msgid ""
"Other than influencing the build process, variants are often used to specify "
"optional :ref:`dependencies of a package <dependencies>`. For example, a "
"package may depend on another package only if a certain variant is enabled:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1408
msgid ""
"class Hdf5(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"szip\", default=False, description=\"Enable szip support\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"szip\", when=\"+szip\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1415
msgid ""
"In this case, ``szip`` is modeled as an optional dependency of ``hdf5``, and "
"users can run ``spack install hdf5 +szip`` to enable it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1418
msgid "Single-valued variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1420
msgid ""
"Other than boolean variants, Spack supports single- and multi-valued "
"variants that can take one or more *string* values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1422
msgid ""
"To define a *single-valued* variant, simply pass a tuple of possible values "
"to the ``variant`` directive, together with ``multi=False``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1424
msgid ""
"class Blis(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\n"
"        \"threads\",\n"
"        default=\"none\",\n"
"        values=(\"pthreads\", \"openmp\", \"none\"),\n"
"        multi=False,\n"
"        description=\"Multithreading support\",\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1436
msgid "This allows users to ``spack install blis threads=openmp``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1438
msgid ""
"In the example above the argument ``multi=False`` indicates that only a "
"**single value** can be selected at a time. This constraint is enforced by "
"the solver, and an error is emitted if a user specifies two or more values "
"at the same time:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1441
msgid ""
"$ spack spec blis threads=openmp,pthreads\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"blis threads=openmp,pthreads\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"==> Error: multiple values are not allowed for variant \"threads\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1454
msgid ""
"In the example above, the value ``threads=none`` is a variant value like any "
"other, and means that *no value is selected*. In Spack, all variants have to "
"have a value, so ``none`` was chosen as a *convention* to indicate that no "
"value is selected."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1458
msgid "Multi-valued variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1460
msgid ""
"Like single-valued variants, multi-valued variants take one or more *string* "
"values, but allow users to select multiple values at the same time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1462
msgid "To define a *multi-valued* variant, simply pass ``multi=True`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1464
msgid ""
"class Gcc(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\n"
"        \"languages\",\n"
"        default=\"c,c++,fortran\",\n"
"        values=(\"ada\", \"brig\", \"c\", \"c++\", \"fortran\", \"objc\"),\n"
"        multi=True,\n"
"        description=\"Compilers and runtime libraries to build\",\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1476
msgid ""
"This allows users to run ``spack install languages=c,c++``, where the values "
"are separated by commas."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1480
msgid "Advanced validation of multi-valued variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1482
msgid ""
"As noted above, the value ``none`` is a value like any other, which raises "
"the question: what if a variant allows multiple values to be selected, *or* "
"none at all? Naively, one might think that this can be achieved by simply "
"creating a multi-valued variant that includes the value ``none``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1485
msgid ""
"class Adios(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\n"
"        \"staging\",\n"
"        values=(\"dataspaces\", \"flexpath\", \"none\"),\n"
"        multi=True,\n"
"        description=\"Enable dataspaces and/or flexpath staging "
"transports\",\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1496
msgid ""
"but this does not prevent users from selecting the nonsensical option "
"``staging=dataspaces,none``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1498
msgid ""
"In these cases, more advanced validation logic is required to prevent "
"``none`` from being selected along with any other value. Spack provides two "
"validator functions to help with this, which can be passed to the "
"``values=`` argument of the ``variant`` directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1501
msgid ""
"The first validator function is :py:func:`~spack.package."
"any_combination_of`, which can be used as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1503
msgid ""
"class Adios(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\n"
"        \"staging\",\n"
"        values=any_combination_of(\"flexpath\", \"dataspaces\"),\n"
"        description=\"Enable dataspaces and/or flexpath staging "
"transports\",\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1513
msgid ""
"This solves the issue by allowing the user to select either any combination "
"of the values ``flexpath`` and ``dataspaces``, or ``none``. In other words, "
"users can specify ``staging=none`` to select nothing, or any of "
"``staging=dataspaces``, ``staging=flexpath``, and ``staging=dataspaces,"
"flexpath``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1516
msgid ""
"The second validator function :py:func:`~spack.package.disjoint_sets` "
"generalizes this idea further:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1518
msgid ""
"class Mvapich2(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\n"
"        \"process_managers\",\n"
"        description=\"List of the process managers to activate\",\n"
"        values=disjoint_sets((\"auto\",), (\"slurm\",), (\"hydra\", "
"\"gforker\", \"remshell\"))\n"
"        .prohibit_empty_set()\n"
"        .with_error(\"'slurm' or 'auto' cannot be activated along with other "
"process managers\")\n"
"        .with_default(\"auto\")\n"
"        .with_non_feature_values(\"auto\"),\n"
"    )"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1532
msgid ""
"In this case, examples of valid options are ``process_managers=auto``, "
"``process_managers=slurm``, and ``process_managers=hydra,remshell``, whereas "
"``process_managers=slurm,hydra`` is invalid, as it picks values from two "
"different sets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1534
msgid ""
"Both validator functions return a :py:class:`~spack.variant."
"DisjointSetsOfValues` object, which defines chaining methods to further "
"customize the behavior of the variant."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1539
msgid "Conditional Possible Values"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1541
msgid ""
"There are cases where a variant may take multiple values, and the list of "
"allowed values expands over time. Consider, for instance, the C++ standard "
"with which we might compile Boost, which can take one of multiple possible "
"values with the latest standards only available for more recent versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1544
msgid ""
"To model a similar situation we can use *conditional possible values* in the "
"variant declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1546
msgid ""
"variant(\n"
"    \"cxxstd\",\n"
"    default=\"98\",\n"
"    values=(\n"
"        \"98\",\n"
"        \"11\",\n"
"        \"14\",\n"
"        # C++17 is not supported by Boost < 1.63.0.\n"
"        conditional(\"17\", when=\"@1.63.0:\"),\n"
"        # C++20/2a is not supported by Boost < 1.73.0\n"
"        conditional(\"2a\", \"2b\", when=\"@1.73.0:\"),\n"
"    ),\n"
"    multi=False,\n"
"    description=\"Use the specified C++ standard when building.\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1565
msgid ""
"The snippet above allows ``98``, ``11`` and ``14`` as unconditional possible "
"values for the ``cxxstd`` variant, while ``17`` requires a version greater "
"than or equal to ``1.63.0`` and both ``2a`` and ``2b`` require a version "
"greater than or equal to ``1.73.0``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1569
msgid "Conditional Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1571
msgid ""
"As new versions of packages are released, optional features may be added and "
"removed. Sometimes, features are only available for a particular platform or "
"architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1574
msgid ""
"To reduce the visual clutter in specs, packages can define variants "
"*conditionally* using a ``when`` clause. The variant will only be present on "
"specs that satisfy this condition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1577
msgid ""
"For example, the following package defines a variant ``bar`` that exists "
"only when it is at version 2.0 or higher, and a variant ``baz`` that exists "
"only on the Darwin platform:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1579
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"bar\", default=False, when=\"@2.0:\", ...)\n"
"    variant(\"baz\", default=True, when=\"platform=darwin\", ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1586
msgid ""
"Do note that conditional variants can also be a source of confusion. In "
"Spack, the absence of a variant is different from it being disabled. For "
"example, a user might run ``spack install foo ~bar``, expecting it to allow "
"version 1.0 (which does not have the ``bar`` feature) and version 2.0 (with "
"the feature disabled). However, the constraint ``~bar`` tells Spack that the "
"``bar`` variant *must exist* and be disabled. This forces Spack to select "
"version 2.0 or higher, where the variant is defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1593
msgid "Sticky Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1595
msgid ""
"The variant directive can be marked as ``sticky`` by setting the "
"corresponding argument to ``True``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1597
msgid "variant(\"bar\", default=False, sticky=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1601
msgid ""
"A ``sticky`` variant differs from a regular one in that it is always set to "
"either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1603
msgid "An explicit value appearing in a spec literal or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1604
msgid "Its default value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1606
msgid ""
"The concretizer thus is not free to pick an alternate value to work around "
"conflicts, but will error out instead. Setting this property on a variant is "
"useful in cases where the variant allows some dangerous or controversial "
"options (e.g., using unsupported versions of a compiler for a library) and "
"the packager wants to ensure that allowing these options is done on purpose "
"by the user, rather than automatically by the solver."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1611
msgid "Overriding Variants"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1613
msgid ""
"Packages may override variants for several reasons, most often to change the "
"default from a variant defined in a parent class or to change the conditions "
"under which a variant is present on the spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1615
msgid ""
"When a variant is defined multiple times, whether in the same package file "
"or in a subclass and a superclass, the last definition is used for all "
"attributes **except** for the ``when`` clauses. The ``when`` clauses are "
"accumulated through all invocations, and the variant is present on the spec "
"if any of the accumulated conditions are satisfied."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1618
msgid "For example, consider the following package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1620
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"bar\", default=False, when=\"@1.0\", description=\"help1\")\n"
"    variant(\"bar\", default=True, when=\"platform=darwin\", "
"description=\"help2\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1628
msgid ""
"This package ``foo`` has a variant ``bar`` when the spec satisfies either "
"``@1.0`` or ``platform=darwin``, but not for other platforms at other "
"versions. The default for this variant, when it is present, is always "
"``True``, regardless of which condition of the variant is satisfied. This "
"allows packages to override variants in packages or build system classes "
"from which they inherit, by modifying the variant values without modifying "
"the ``when`` clause. It also allows a package to implement ``or`` semantics "
"for a variant ``when`` clause by duplicating the variant definition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1636
msgid "Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1638
msgid ""
"We've covered how to build a simple package, but what if one package relies "
"on another package to build? How do you express that in a package file? And "
"how do you refer to the other package in the build script for your own "
"package?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1642
msgid ""
"Spack makes this relatively easy. Let's take a look at the ``libdwarf`` "
"package to see how it's done:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1645
msgid ""
"class Libdwarf(Package):\n"
"    homepage = \"http://www.prevanders.net/dwarf.html\"\n"
"    url = \"http://www.prevanders.net/libdwarf-20130729.tar.gz\"\n"
"    list_url = homepage\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"20130729\", "
"sha256=\"092fcfbbcfca3b5be7ae1b5e58538e92c35ab273ae13664fed0d67484c8e78a6\")\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"libelf\")\n"
"\n"
"    def install(self, spec, prefix): ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1662
msgid "``depends_on()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1664
msgid ""
"The highlighted ``depends_on(\"libelf\")`` call tells Spack that it needs to "
"build and install the ``libelf`` package before it builds ``libdwarf``. This "
"means that in your ``install()`` method, you are guaranteed that ``libelf`` "
"has been built and installed successfully, so you can rely on it for your "
"``libdwarf`` build."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1670
msgid "Dependency specs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1672
msgid ""
"``depends_on`` doesn't just take the name of another package. It can take a "
"full spec as well. This means that you can restrict the versions or other "
"configuration options of ``libelf`` that ``libdwarf`` will build with. For "
"example, suppose that in the ``libdwarf`` package you write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1677
msgid "depends_on(\"libelf@0.8\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1681
msgid ""
"Now ``libdwarf`` will require ``libelf`` in the range ``0.8``, which "
"includes patch versions ``0.8.1``, ``0.8.2``, etc. Apart from version "
"restrictions, you can also specify variants if this package requires "
"optional features of the dependency."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1684
msgid "depends_on(\"libelf@0.8 +parser +pic\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1688
msgid ""
"Both users *and* package authors use the same spec syntax to refer to "
"different package configurations. Users use the spec syntax on the command "
"line to find installed packages or to install packages with particular "
"constraints, and package authors can use specs to describe relationships "
"between packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1694
msgid "Specifying backward and forward compatibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1696
msgid ""
"Packages are often compatible with a range of versions of their "
"dependencies. This is typically referred to as backward and forward "
"compatibility. Spack allows you to specify this in the ``depends_on`` "
"directive using version ranges."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1700
msgid ""
"**Backward compatibility** means that the package requires at least a "
"certain version of its dependency:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1702
msgid "depends_on(\"python@3.10:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1706
msgid ""
"In this case, the package requires Python 3.10 or newer, as specified in the "
"project's :file:`pyproject.toml`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1708
msgid ""
"Commonly, packages drop support for older versions of a dependency as they "
"release new versions. In Spack you can conveniently add every backward "
"compatibility rule as a separate line:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1711
msgid ""
"# backward compatibility with Python\n"
"depends_on(\"python@3.8:\")\n"
"depends_on(\"python@3.9:\", when=\"@1.2:\")\n"
"depends_on(\"python@3.10:\", when=\"@1.4:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1718
msgid ""
"This means that in general we need Python 3.8 or newer; from version 1.2 "
"onwards we need Python 3.9 or newer; from version 1.4 onwards we need Python "
"3.10 or newer. Notice that it's fine to have overlapping ranges in the "
"``when`` clauses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1721
msgid ""
"**Forward compatibility** means that the package requires at most a certain "
"version of its dependency. Forward compatibility rules are necessary when "
"there are breaking changes in the dependency that the package cannot handle. "
"In Spack we often add forward compatibility bounds only at the time a new, "
"breaking version of a dependency is released. As with backward "
"compatibility, it is typical to see a list of forward compatibility bounds "
"in a package file as separate lines:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1726
msgid ""
"# forward compatibility with Python\n"
"depends_on(\"python@:3.12\", when=\"@:1.10\")\n"
"depends_on(\"python@:3.13\", when=\"@:1.12\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1732
msgid ""
"Notice how the ``:`` now appears before the version number both in the "
"dependency and in the ``when`` clause. This tells Spack that in general we "
"need Python 3.13 or older up to version ``1.12.x``, and up to version ``1.10."
"x`` we need Python 3.12 or older. Said differently, forward compatibility "
"with Python 3.13 was added in version 1.11, while version 1.13 added forward "
"compatibility with Python 3.14."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1736
msgid ""
"Notice that a version range ``@:3.12`` includes *any* patch version number "
"``3.12.x``, which is often useful when specifying forward compatibility "
"bounds."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1738
msgid ""
"So far we have seen open-ended version ranges, which is by far the most "
"common use case. It is also possible to specify both a lower and an upper "
"bound on the version of a dependency, like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1741
msgid "depends_on(\"python@3.10:3.12\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1745
msgid ""
"There is short syntax to specify that a package is compatible with say any "
"``3.x`` version:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1747
msgid "depends_on(\"python@3\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1751
msgid ""
"The above is equivalent to ``depends_on(\"python@3:3\")``, which means at "
"least Python version 3 and at most any ``3.x.y`` version."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1753
msgid ""
"In very rare cases, you may need to specify an exact version, for example if "
"you need to distinguish between ``3.2`` and ``3.2.1``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1755
msgid "depends_on(\"pkg@=3.2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1759
msgid ""
"But in general, you should try to use version ranges as much as possible, so "
"that custom suffixes are included too. The above example can be rewritten in "
"terms of ranges as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1762
msgid "depends_on(\"pkg@3.2:3.2.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1766
msgid ""
"A spec can contain a version list of ranges and individual versions "
"separated by commas. For example, if you need Boost 1.59.0 or newer, but "
"there are known issues with 1.64.0, 1.65.0, and 1.66.0, you can say:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1769
msgid "depends_on(\"boost@1.59.0:1.63,1.65.1,1.67.0:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1773
msgid ""
"or, if those particular versions are excluded due to bugs rather than "
"removed and reintroduced features:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1775
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"boost@1.59.0:\")\n"
"conflicts(\"^boost@1.64.0,1.65.0,1.66.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1780
msgid "Always specify version ranges with an open-world assumption:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1782
msgid ""
"all \"ground truths\" about exclusions and inclusions (e.g., versions with "
"features added or removed) must satisfy the range, and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1783
msgid "no potential but unknown versions are excluded from the range."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1785
msgid ""
"This practice avoids overconstraining version ranges, which can lead to "
"concretization errors, and ensures that every version in a package is "
"*meaningful* and not just *incidental* (i.e., based on the version you "
"happened to test). In the above example, the project has presumably "
"documented (with pyproject.toml, CMakeLists.txt, or release notes) that "
"``@:1.58`` are incompatible, and it is known from testing that ``@1.67`` is "
"compatible. It is *not* known whether future versions ``@1.68:`` are "
"incompatible, so they must be included by the range. If and when future "
"versions are known incompatible, the version range should be constrained "
"with an upper bound."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1793
msgid "Dependency types"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1795
msgid ""
"Not all dependencies are created equal, and Spack allows you to specify "
"exactly what kind of a dependency you need. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1798
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"cmake\", type=\"build\")\n"
"depends_on(\"py-numpy\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))\n"
"depends_on(\"libelf\", type=(\"build\", \"link\"))\n"
"depends_on(\"py-pytest\", type=\"test\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1805
msgid "The following dependency types are available:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1807
msgid ""
"**build**: the dependency will be added to the ``PATH`` and ``PYTHONPATH`` "
"at build-time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1808
msgid ""
"**link**: the dependency will be added to Spack's compiler wrappers, "
"automatically injecting the appropriate linker flags, including ``-I``, ``-"
"L``, and RPATH/RUNPATH handling."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1809
msgid ""
"**run**: the dependency will be added to the ``PATH`` and ``PYTHONPATH`` at "
"run-time. This is true for both ``spack load`` and the module files Spack "
"writes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1811
msgid ""
"**test**: the dependency will be added to the ``PATH`` and ``PYTHONPATH`` at "
"build-time. The only difference between \"build\" and \"test\" is that test "
"dependencies are only built if the user requests unit tests with ``spack "
"install --test``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1814
msgid ""
"One of the advantages of the ``build`` dependency type is that although the "
"dependency needs to be installed in order for the package to be built, it "
"can be uninstalled without concern afterwards. ``link`` and ``run`` disallow "
"this because uninstalling the dependency would break the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1817
msgid ""
"``build``, ``link``, and ``run`` dependencies all affect the hash of Spack "
"packages (along with ``sha256`` sums of patches and archives used to build "
"the package, and a `canonical hash <https://github.com/spack/spack/"
"pull/28156>`_ of the ``package.py`` recipes). ``test`` dependencies do not "
"affect the package hash, as they are only used to construct a test "
"environment *after* building and installing a given package installation. "
"Older versions of Spack did not include build dependencies in the hash, but "
"this has been `fixed <https://github.com/spack/spack/pull/28504>`_ as of |"
"Spack v0.18|_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1824
msgid ""
"If the dependency type is not specified, Spack uses a default of "
"``(\"build\", \"link\")``. This is the common case for compiler languages. "
"Non-compiled packages like Python modules commonly use ``(\"build\", "
"\"run\")``. This means that the compiler wrappers don't need to inject the "
"dependency's ``prefix/lib`` directory, but the package needs to be in "
"``PATH`` and ``PYTHONPATH`` during the build process and later when a user "
"wants to run the package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1830
msgid "Conditional dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1832
msgid ""
"You may have a package that only requires a dependency under certain "
"conditions. For example, you may have a package with optional MPI support. "
"You would then provide a variant to reflect that the feature is optional and "
"specify the MPI dependency only applies when MPI support is enabled. In that "
"case, you could say something like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1837
msgid ""
"variant(\"mpi\", default=False, description=\"Enable MPI support\")\n"
"\n"
"depends_on(\"mpi\", when=\"+mpi\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1844
msgid ""
"Suppose that, starting from version 3, the above package also has optional "
"`Trilinos` support. Furthermore, you want to ensure that when `Trilinos` "
"support is enabled, the package can be built both with and without MPI. "
"Further suppose you require a version of `Trilinos` no older than 12.6. In "
"that case, the `trilinos` variant and dependency directives would be:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1849
msgid ""
"variant(\"trilinos\", default=False, description=\"Enable Trilinos "
"support\")\n"
"\n"
"depends_on(\"trilinos@12.6:\", when=\"@3: +trilinos\")\n"
"depends_on(\"trilinos@12.6: +mpi\", when=\"@3: +trilinos +mpi\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1857
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you could use the `when` context manager to equivalently "
"specify the `trilinos` variant dependencies as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1859
msgid ""
"with when(\"@3: +trilinos\"):\n"
"    depends_on(\"trilinos@12.6:\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"trilinos +mpi\", when=\"+mpi\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1866
msgid ""
"The argument to ``when`` in either case can include any Spec constraints "
"that are supported on the command line using the same :ref:`syntax <sec-"
"specs>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1870
msgid ""
"If a dependency isn't typically used, you can save time by making it "
"conditional since Spack will not build the dependency unless it is required "
"for the Spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1876
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2398
msgid "Dependency patching"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1878
msgid ""
"Some packages maintain special patches on their dependencies, either to add "
"new features or to fix bugs. This typically makes a package harder to "
"maintain, and we encourage developers to upstream (contribute back) their "
"changes rather than maintaining patches. However, in some cases it's not "
"possible to upstream. Maybe the dependency's developers don't accept "
"changes, or maybe they just haven't had time to integrate them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1883
msgid ""
"For times like these, Spack's ``depends_on`` directive can optionally take a "
"patch or list of patches:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1885
msgid ""
"class SpecialTool(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\"binutils\", patches=\"special-binutils-feature.patch\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1892
msgid ""
"Here, the ``special-tool`` package requires a special feature in "
"``binutils``, so it provides an extra ``patches=<filename>`` keyword "
"argument. This is similar to the `patch directive <patching_>`_, with one "
"small difference. Here, ``special-tool`` is responsible for the patch, so it "
"should live in ``special-tool``'s directory in the package repository, not "
"the ``binutils`` directory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1896
msgid ""
"If you need something more sophisticated, you can nest a ``patch()`` "
"directive inside ``depends_on``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1898
msgid ""
"class SpecialTool(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\n"
"        \"binutils\",\n"
"        patches=patch(\n"
"            \"special-binutils-feature.patch\", level=3, when=\"@:1.3\"  # "
"condition on binutils\n"
"        ),\n"
"        when=\"@2.0:\",  # condition on special-tool\n"
"    )\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1911
msgid ""
"Note that there are two optional ``when`` conditions here -- one on the "
"``patch`` directive and the other on ``depends_on``. The condition in the "
"``patch`` directive applies to ``binutils`` (the package being patched), "
"while the condition in ``depends_on`` applies to ``special-tool``. See "
"`patch directive <patching_>`_ for details on all the arguments the "
"``patch`` directive can take."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1915
msgid ""
"Finally, if you need *multiple* patches on a dependency, you can provide a "
"list for ``patches``, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1917
msgid ""
"class SpecialTool(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\n"
"        \"binutils\",\n"
"        patches=[\n"
"            \"binutils-bugfix1.patch\",\n"
"            \"binutils-bugfix2.patch\",\n"
"            patch(\n"
"                \"https://example.com/special-binutils-feature.patch\",\n"
"                sha256=\"252c0af58be3d90e5dc5e0d16658434c9efa5d20a5df6c10bf72c2d77f780866\",\n"
"                when=\"@:1.3\",\n"
"            ),\n"
"        ],\n"
"        when=\"@2.0:\",\n"
"    )\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1936
msgid ""
"As with ``patch`` directives, patches are applied in the order they appear "
"in the package file (or in this case, in the list)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1940
msgid ""
"You may wonder whether dependency patching will interfere with other "
"packages that depend on ``binutils``. It won't."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1943
msgid ""
"As described in :ref:`patching`, Patching a package adds the ``sha256`` of "
"the patch to the package's spec, which means it will have a *different* "
"unique hash than other versions without the patch. The patched version "
"coexists with unpatched versions, and Spack's support for :ref:"
"`handling_rpaths` guarantees that each installation finds the right version. "
"If two packages depend on ``binutils`` patched *the same* way, they can both "
"use a single installation of ``binutils``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1950
msgid "Virtual dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1952
msgid ""
"In some cases, more than one package can satisfy another package's "
"dependency. One way this can happen is if a package depends on a particular "
"*interface*, but there are multiple *implementations* of the interface, and "
"the package could be built with any of them. A *very* common interface in "
"HPC is the `Message Passing Interface (MPI) <http://www.mcs.anl.gov/research/"
"projects/mpi/>`_, which is used in many large-scale parallel applications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1956
msgid ""
"MPI has several different implementations (e.g., `MPICH <http://www.mpich."
"org>`_, `OpenMPI <http://www.open-mpi.org>`_, and `MVAPICH <http://mvapich."
"cse.ohio-state.edu>`_) and scientific applications can be built with any one "
"of them. Many package managers handle interfaces like this by requiring many "
"variations of the package recipe for each implementation of MPI, e.g., "
"``foo``, ``foo-mvapich``, ``foo-mpich``. In Spack every package is defined "
"in a single ``package.py`` file, and avoids the combinatorial explosion "
"through *virtual dependencies*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1961
msgid "``provides``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1963
msgid ""
"In Spack, ``mpi`` is handled as a *virtual package*. A package like "
"``mpileaks`` can depend on the virtual ``mpi`` just like any other package, "
"by supplying a ``depends_on`` call in the package definition. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1967
msgid ""
"class Mpileaks(Package):\n"
"    homepage = \"https://github.com/hpc/mpileaks\"\n"
"    url = \"https://github.com/hpc/mpileaks/releases/download/v1.0/"
"mpileaks-1.0.tar.gz\"\n"
"\n"
"    version(\"1.0\", "
"sha256=\"768c71d785bf6bbbf8c4d6af6582041f2659027140a962cd0c55b11eddfd5e3d\")\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"adept-utils\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"callpath\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1981
msgid ""
"Here, ``callpath`` and ``adept-utils`` are concrete packages, but there is "
"no actual package for ``mpi``, so we say it is a *virtual* package. The "
"syntax of ``depends_on`` is the same for both. If we look inside the package "
"file of an MPI implementation, say MPICH, we'll see something like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1985
msgid ""
"class Mpich(Package):\n"
"    provides(\"mpi\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1991
msgid ""
"The ``provides(\"mpi\")`` call tells Spack that the ``mpich`` package can be "
"used to satisfy the dependency of any package that ``depends_on(\"mpi\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1994
msgid "Providing multiple virtuals simultaneously"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1996
msgid ""
"Packages can provide more than one virtual dependency. Sometimes, due to "
"implementation details, there are subsets of those virtuals that need to be "
"provided together by the same package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:1999
msgid ""
"A well-known example is ``openblas``, which provides both the ``lapack`` and "
"``blas`` API in a single ``libopenblas`` library. A package that needs "
"``lapack`` and ``blas`` must either use ``openblas`` to provide both, or not "
"use ``openblas`` at all. It cannot pick one or the other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2003
msgid ""
"To express this constraint in a package, the two virtual dependencies must "
"be listed in the same ``provides`` directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2005
msgid "provides(\"blas\", \"lapack\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2009
msgid ""
"This makes it impossible to select ``openblas`` as a provider for one of the "
"two virtual dependencies and not for the other. If you try to, Spack will "
"report an error:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2012
msgid ""
"$ spack spec netlib-scalapack  ^[virtuals=lapack] openblas ^[virtuals=blas] "
"atlas\n"
"==> Error: concretization failed for the following reasons:\n"
"\n"
"   1. Package 'openblas' needs to provide both 'lapack' and 'blas' together, "
"but provides only 'lapack'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2020
msgid "Versioned Interfaces"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2022
msgid ""
"Just as you can pass a spec to ``depends_on``, so can you pass a spec to "
"``provides`` to add constraints. This allows Spack to support the notion of "
"*versioned interfaces*. The MPI standard has gone through many revisions, "
"each with new functions added, and each revision of the standard has a "
"version number. Some packages may require a recent implementation that "
"supports MPI-3 functions, but some MPI versions may only provide up to "
"MPI-2. Others may need MPI 2.1 or higher. You can indicate this by adding a "
"version constraint to the spec passed to ``provides``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2029
msgid "provides(\"mpi@:2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2033
msgid ""
"Suppose that the above ``provides`` call is in the ``mpich2`` package. This "
"says that ``mpich2`` provides MPI support *up to* version 2, but if a "
"package ``depends_on(\"mpi@3\")``, then Spack will *not* build that package "
"with ``mpich2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2036
msgid ""
"Currently, names and versions are the only spec components supported for "
"virtual packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2039
msgid "``provides when``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2041
msgid ""
"The same package may provide different versions of an interface depending on "
"*its* version. Above, we simplified the ``provides`` call in ``mpich`` to "
"make the explanation easier. In reality, this is how ``mpich`` calls "
"``provides``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2045
msgid ""
"provides(\"mpi@:3\", when=\"@3:\")\n"
"provides(\"mpi@:1\", when=\"@1:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2050
msgid ""
"The ``when`` argument to ``provides`` allows you to specify optional "
"constraints on the *providing* package, or the *provider*. The provider only "
"provides the declared virtual spec when *it* matches the constraints in the "
"``when`` clause. Here, when ``mpich`` is at version 3 or higher, it provides "
"MPI up to version 3. When ``mpich`` is at version 1 or higher, it provides "
"the MPI virtual package at version 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2055
msgid ""
"The ``when`` qualifier ensures that Spack selects a suitably high version of "
"``mpich`` to satisfy some other package that ``depends_on`` a particular "
"version of MPI. It will also prevent a user from building with too low a "
"version of ``mpich``. For example, suppose the package ``foo`` declares this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2059
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\"mpi@2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2065
msgid "Suppose a user invokes ``spack install`` like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2067
msgid "$ spack install foo ^mpich@1.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2071
msgid ""
"Spack will fail with a constraint violation, because the version of MPICH "
"requested is too low for the ``mpi`` requirement in ``foo``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2076
msgid "Language and compiler dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2078
msgid ""
"Whenever you use ``spack create`` to create a new package, Spack scans the "
"package's source code and heuristically adds *language dependencies*, which "
"look like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2080
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"c\", type=\"build\")\n"
"depends_on(\"cxx\", type=\"build\")\n"
"depends_on(\"fortran\", type=\"build\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2086
msgid ""
"The languages ``c``, ``cxx`` and ``fortran`` are **virtuals provided by "
"compiler packages**, such as ``gcc``, ``llvm``, or ``intel-oneapi-"
"compilers``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2088
msgid ""
"When you concretize a package that depends on ``c``, Spack will select a "
"compiler for it that provides the ``c`` virtual package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2090
msgid ""
"Typically one compiler will be used to provide all languages, but Spack is "
"allowed to create a mixed toolchain. For example, the ``c`` compiler could "
"be ``clang`` from the ``llvm`` package, whereas the ``fortran`` compiler "
"could be ``gfortran`` from the ``gcc``. This means that language "
"dependencies translate to one or more compiler packages as build "
"dependencies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2098
msgid "Conflicts"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2100
msgid ""
"Sometimes packages have known bugs, or limitations, that would prevent them "
"from concretizing or building usable software. Spack makes it possible to "
"express such constraints with the ``conflicts`` directive, which takes a "
"spec that is known to cause a conflict and optional ``when`` and ``msg`` "
"arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2103
msgid "The ``when`` argument is a spec that triggers the conflict."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2105
msgid ""
"The ``msg`` argument allows you to provide a custom error message that Spack "
"prints when the spec to be installed satisfies the conflict spec and "
"``when`` trigger."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2107
msgid "Adding the following to a package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2109
msgid ""
"conflicts(\n"
"    \"%intel-oneapi-compilers@:2024\",\n"
"    when=\"@:1.2\",\n"
"    msg=\"known bug when using Intel oneAPI compilers through v2024\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2117
msgid ""
"expresses that the current package *cannot be built* with Intel oneAPI "
"compilers *up through any version* ``2024`` *when trying to install the "
"package with a version up to* ``1.2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2119
msgid ""
"If the ``when`` argument is omitted, then the conflict is *always triggered* "
"for specs satisfying the conflict spec. For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2122
msgid ""
"conflicts(\"+cuda+rocm\", msg=\"Cannot build with both cuda and rocm "
"enabled\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2126
msgid "means the package cannot be installed with both variants enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2128
msgid ""
"Similarly, a conflict can be based on where the build is being performed. "
"For example,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2131
msgid ""
"for os in [\"ventura\", \"monterey\", \"bigsur\"]:\n"
"    conflicts(f\"platform=darwin os={os}\", msg=f\"{os} is not supported\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2136
msgid ""
"means the package cannot be built on a Mac running Ventura, Monterey, or Big "
"Sur."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2140
msgid ""
"These examples illustrate a few of the types of constraints that can be "
"specified. Conflict and ``when`` specs can constrain the compiler, :ref:"
"`version <version_constraints>`, :ref:`variants <basic-variants>`, :ref:"
"`architecture <architecture_specifiers>`, :ref:`dependencies "
"<dependency_specs>`, and more. See :ref:`sec-specs` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2148
msgid "Requires"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2150
msgid ""
"Sometimes packages can be built only with specific options. In those cases "
"the ``requires`` directive can be used. It allows for complex conditions "
"involving more than a single spec through the ability to specify multiple "
"required specs before keyword arguments. The same optional ``when`` and "
"``msg`` arguments as ``conflicts`` are supported (see :ref:"
"`packaging_conflicts`). The directive also supports a ``policy`` argument "
"for determining how the multiple required specs apply. Values for ``policy`` "
"may be either ``any_of`` or ``one_of`` (default) and have the same semantics "
"described for their equivalents in :ref:`package-requirements`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2159
msgid ""
"We recommend that the ``policy`` argument be explicitly specified when "
"multiple specs are used with the directive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2161
msgid ""
"For example, suppose a package can only be built with Apple Clang on Darwin. "
"This requirement would be specified as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2164
msgid ""
"requires(\n"
"    \"%apple-clang\",\n"
"    when=\"platform=darwin\",\n"
"    msg=\"builds only with Apple Clang compiler on Darwin\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2172
msgid "Similarly, suppose a package only builds for the ``x86_64`` target:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2174
msgid ""
"requires(\"target=x86_64:\", msg=\"package is only available on x86_64\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2178
msgid ""
"Or the package must be built with a GCC or Clang that supports C++ 20, which "
"you could ensure by adding the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2180
msgid ""
"requires(\n"
"    \"%gcc@10:\",\n"
"    \"%clang@16:\",\n"
"    policy=\"one_of\",\n"
"    msg=\"builds only with a GCC or Clang that support C++ 20\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2191
msgid ""
"These examples show only a few of the constraints that can be specified. "
"Required and ``when`` specs can constrain the compiler, :ref:`version "
"<version_constraints>`, :ref:`variants <basic-variants>`, :ref:`architecture "
"<architecture_specifiers>`, :ref:`dependencies <dependency_specs>`, and "
"more. See :ref:`sec-specs` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2199
msgid "Patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2201
msgid ""
"Depending on the host architecture, package version, known bugs, or other "
"issues, you may need to patch your software to get it to build correctly. "
"Like many other package systems, Spack allows you to store patches alongside "
"your package files and apply them to source code after it's downloaded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2205
msgid "``patch``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2207
msgid ""
"You can specify patches in your package file with the ``patch()`` directive. "
"The first argument can be either the filename or URL of the patch file to be "
"applied to your source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2212
msgid ""
"Use of a URL is preferred over maintaining patch files in the package "
"repository. This helps reduce the size of the package repository, which can "
"become an issue for those with limited space (or allocations)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2216
msgid "Filename patch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2218
msgid ""
"You can supply the name of the patch file. For example, a simple conditional "
"``patch`` based on a file for the ``mvapich2`` package looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2221
msgid ""
"class Mvapich2(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    patch(\"ad_lustre_rwcontig_open_source.patch\", when=\"@1.9:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2227
msgid ""
"This patch will only be applied when attempting to install the package at "
"version ``1.9`` or newer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2229
msgid ""
"When a filename is provided, the patch needs to live within the Spack source "
"tree. The above patch file lives with the package file within the package "
"repository directory structure in the following location:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2232
msgid ""
"spack_repo/builtin/packages/\n"
"    mvapich2/\n"
"        package.py\n"
"        ad_lustre_rwcontig_open_source.patch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2240
msgid "URL patch file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2242
msgid ""
"If you supply a URL instead of a filename you have two options: patch file "
"URL or commit patch file URL. In either case, you must supply a checksum. "
"Spack requires the ``sha256`` hash so that different patches applied to the "
"same package will have unique identifiers. Patches will be fetched from "
"their URLs, checked, and applied to your source code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2249
msgid ""
"To ensure consistency, a ``sha256`` checksum must be provided for the patch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2251
msgid ""
"You can use the GNU utils ``sha256sum`` or the macOS ``shasum -a 256`` "
"commands to generate a checksum for a patch file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2253
msgid ""
"Here is an example of specifying the unconditional use of a patch file URL:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2255
msgid ""
"patch(\n"
"    \"http://www.nwchem-sw.org/images/Tddft_mxvec20.patch\",\n"
"    sha256=\"252c0af58be3d90e5dc5e0d16658434c9efa5d20a5df6c10bf72c2d77f780866\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2262
msgid ""
"Sometimes you can specify the patch file associated with a repository "
"commit. For example, GitHub allows you to reference the commit in the name "
"of the patch file through a URL in the form ``https://github.com/<owner>/"
"<repository>/commit/<commit_SHA>.patch``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2265
msgid "Below is an example of specifying a conditional commit patch:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2267
msgid ""
"patch(\n"
"    \"https://github.com/ornladios/ADIOS/"
"commit/17aee8aeed64612cd8cfa0b949147091a5525bbe.patch?full_index=1\",\n"
"    sha256=\"aea47e56013b57c2d5d36e23e0ae6010541c3333a84003784437768c2e350b05\",\n"
"    when=\"@1.12.0: +mpi\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2275
msgid ""
"In this case the patch is only processed when attempting to install version "
"``1.12.0`` or higher of the package when the package's ``mpi`` variant is "
"enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2284
msgid "Compressed patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2286
msgid ""
"Spack can also handle compressed patches. If you use these, Spack needs a "
"little more help. Specifically, it needs *two* checksums: the ``sha256`` of "
"the patch and ``archive_sha256`` for the compressed archive. "
"``archive_sha256`` helps Spack ensure that the downloaded file is not "
"corrupted or malicious, before running it through a tool like ``tar`` or "
"``zip``. The ``sha256`` of the patch is still required so that it can be "
"included in specs. Providing it in the package file ensures that Spack won't "
"have to download and decompress patches it won't end up using at install "
"time. Both the archive and patch checksum are checked when patch archives "
"are downloaded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2294
msgid ""
"patch(\n"
"    \"http://www.nwchem-sw.org/images/Tddft_mxvec20.patch.gz\",\n"
"    sha256=\"252c0af58be3d90e5dc5e0d16658434c9efa5d20a5df6c10bf72c2d77f780866\",\n"
"    archive_sha256=\"4e8092a161ec6c3a1b5253176fcf33ce7ba23ee2ff27c75dbced589dabacd06e\",\n"
")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2302
msgid "``patch`` keyword arguments are described below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2305
msgid "``sha256``, ``archive_sha256``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2307
msgid ""
"Hashes of downloaded patch and compressed archive, respectively. Only needed "
"for patches fetched from URLs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2311
msgid "``when``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2313
msgid ""
"If supplied, this is a spec that tells Spack when to apply the patch. If the "
"installed package spec matches this spec, the patch will be applied. In our "
"example above, the patch is applied when ``mvapich`` is at version ``1.9`` "
"or higher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2318
msgid "``level``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2320
msgid ""
"This tells Spack how to run the ``patch`` command. By default, the level is "
"1 and Spack runs ``patch -p 1``. If level is 2, Spack will run ``patch -p "
"2``, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2324
msgid ""
"A lot of people are confused by the level, so here's a primer. If you look "
"in your patch file, you may see something like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2327
msgid ""
"--- a/src/mpi/romio/adio/ad_lustre/ad_lustre_rwcontig.c 2013-12-10 "
"12:05:44.806417000 -0800\n"
"+++ b/src/mpi/romio/adio/ad_lustre/ad_lustre_rwcontig.c 2013-12-10 "
"11:53:03.295622000 -0800\n"
"@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@\n"
"  *   Copyright (C) 2008 Sun Microsystems, Lustre group\n"
"  \\*/\n"
"\n"
"-#define _XOPEN_SOURCE 600\n"
"+//#define _XOPEN_SOURCE 600\n"
" #include <stdlib.h>\n"
" #include <malloc.h>\n"
" #include \"ad_lustre.h\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2342
msgid ""
"Lines 1-2 show paths with synthetic ``a/`` and ``b/`` prefixes. These are "
"placeholders for the two ``mvapich2`` source directories that ``diff`` "
"compared when it created the patch file. This is git's default behavior when "
"creating patch files, but other programs may behave differently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2346
msgid ""
"``-p1`` strips off the first level of the prefix in both paths, allowing the "
"patch to be applied from the root of an expanded ``mvapich2`` archive. If "
"you set level to ``2``, it would strip off ``src``, and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2349
msgid ""
"It's generally easier to just structure your patch file so that it applies "
"cleanly with ``-p1``, but if you're using a patch you didn't create "
"yourself, ``level`` can be handy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2352
msgid "``working_dir``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2354
msgid ""
"This tells Spack where to run the ``patch`` command. By default, the working "
"directory is the source path of the stage (``.``). However, sometimes "
"patches are made with respect to a subdirectory and this is where the "
"working directory comes in handy. Internally, the working directory is given "
"to ``patch`` via the ``-d`` option. Let's take the example patch from above "
"and assume for some reason, it can only be downloaded in the following form:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2360
msgid ""
"--- a/romio/adio/ad_lustre/ad_lustre_rwcontig.c 2013-12-10 "
"12:05:44.806417000 -0800\n"
"+++ b/romio/adio/ad_lustre/ad_lustre_rwcontig.c 2013-12-10 "
"11:53:03.295622000 -0800\n"
"@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@\n"
"  *   Copyright (C) 2008 Sun Microsystems, Lustre group\n"
"  \\*/\n"
"\n"
"-#define _XOPEN_SOURCE 600\n"
"+//#define _XOPEN_SOURCE 600\n"
" #include <stdlib.h>\n"
" #include <malloc.h>\n"
" #include \"ad_lustre.h\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2375
msgid ""
"Hence, the patch needs to be applied in the ``src/mpi`` subdirectory, and "
"the ``working_dir=\"src/mpi\"`` option would exactly do that."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2378
msgid "Patch functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2380
msgid ""
"In addition to supplying patch files, you can write a custom function to "
"patch a package's source. For example, the ``py-pyside2`` package contains "
"some custom code for tweaking the way the PySide build handles include files:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2385
msgid ""
"    def patch(self):\n"
"        filter_file(\n"
"            \"=${shiboken_include_dirs}\",\n"
"            \":\".join(\n"
"                [\n"
"                    \"=${shiboken_include_dirs}\",\n"
"                    self.spec[\"qt\"][\"glx\"][\"libglx\"].prefix.include,\n"
"                    self.spec[\"qt\"][\"libxcb\"].prefix.include,\n"
"                ]\n"
"            ),\n"
"            \"sources/pyside2/cmake/Macros/PySideModules.cmake\",\n"
"            string=True,\n"
"        )\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2389
msgid ""
"A ``patch`` function, if present, will be run after patch files are applied "
"and before ``install()`` is run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2391
msgid ""
"You could put this logic in ``install()``, but putting it in a patch "
"function gives you some benefits. First, Spack ensures that the ``patch()`` "
"function is run once per code checkout. That means that if you run install, "
"hit ctrl-C, and run install again, the code in the patch function is only "
"run once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2400
msgid ""
"So far we've covered how the ``patch`` directive can be used by a package to "
"patch *its own* source code. Packages can *also* specify patches to be "
"applied to their dependencies, if they require special modifications. As "
"with all packages in Spack, a patched dependency library can coexist with "
"other versions of that library. See the `section on depends_on "
"<dependency_dependency_patching_>`_ for more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2408
msgid "Inspecting patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2410
msgid ""
"If you want to better understand the patches that Spack applies to your "
"packages, you can do that using ``spack spec``, ``spack find``, and other "
"query commands. Let's look at ``m4``. If you run ``spack spec m4``, you can "
"see the patches that would be applied to ``m4``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2414
msgid ""
"$ spack spec m4\n"
"Input spec\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"m4\n"
"\n"
"Concretized\n"
"--------------------------------\n"
"m4@1.4.18%apple-clang@9.0.0 "
"patches=3877ab548f88597ab2327a2230ee048d2d07ace1062efe81fc92e91b7f39cd00,"
"c0a408fbffb7255fcc75e26bd8edab116fc81d216bfd18b473668b7739a4158e,"
"fc9b61654a3ba1a8d6cd78ce087e7c96366c290bc8d2c299f09828d793b853c8 +sigsegv "
"arch=darwin-highsierra-x86_64\n"
"    ^libsigsegv@2.11%apple-clang@9.0.0 arch=darwin-highsierra-x86_64"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2426
msgid ""
"You can also see patches that have been applied to installed packages with "
"``spack find -v``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2428
msgid ""
"$ spack find -v m4\n"
"==> 1 installed package\n"
"-- darwin-highsierra-x86_64 / apple-clang@9.0.0 -----------------\n"
"m4@1.4.18 "
"patches=3877ab548f88597ab2327a2230ee048d2d07ace1062efe81fc92e91b7f39cd00,"
"c0a408fbffb7255fcc75e26bd8edab116fc81d216bfd18b473668b7739a4158e,"
"fc9b61654a3ba1a8d6cd78ce087e7c96366c290bc8d2c299f09828d793b853c8 +sigsegv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2437
msgid ""
"In both cases above, you can see that the patches' sha256 hashes are stored "
"on the spec as a variant. As mentioned above, this means that you can have "
"multiple, differently-patched versions of a package installed at once."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2440
msgid ""
"You can look up a patch by its sha256 hash (or a short version of it) using "
"the ``spack resource show`` command"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2442
msgid ""
"$ spack resource show 3877ab54\n"
"3877ab548f88597ab2327a2230ee048d2d07ace1062efe81fc92e91b7f39cd00\n"
"    path:       .../spack_repo/builtin/packages/m4/gnulib-pgi.patch\n"
"    applies to: builtin.m4"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2449
msgid ""
"``spack resource show`` looks up downloadable resources from package files "
"by hash and prints out information about them. Above, we see that the "
"``3877ab54`` patch applies to the ``m4`` package. The output also tells us "
"where to find the patch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2453
msgid ""
"Things get more interesting if you want to know about dependency patches. "
"For example, when ``dealii`` is built with ``boost@1.68.0``, it has to patch "
"boost to work correctly. If you didn't know this, you might wonder where the "
"extra boost patches are coming from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2457
msgid ""
"$ spack spec dealii ^boost@1.68.0 ^hdf5+fortran | grep \"\\^boost\"\n"
"    ^boost@1.68.0\n"
"        ^boost@1.68.0%apple-clang@9.0.0+atomic+chrono~clanglibcpp "
"cxxstd=default "
"+date_time~debug+exception+filesystem+graph~icu+iostreams+locale+log+math~mpi+multithreaded~numpy "
"patches=2ab6c72d03dec6a4ae20220a9dfd5c8c572c5294252155b85c6874d97c323199,"
"b37164268f34f7133cbc9a4066ae98fda08adf51e1172223f6a969909216870f "
"~pic+program_options~python+random+regex+serialization+shared+signals~singlethreaded+system~taggedlayout+test+thread+timer~versionedlayout+wave "
"arch=darwin-highsierra-x86_64\n"
"$ spack resource show b37164268\n"
"b37164268f34f7133cbc9a4066ae98fda08adf51e1172223f6a969909216870f\n"
"    path:       .../spack_repo/builtin/packages/dealii/boost_1.68.0.patch\n"
"    applies to: builtin.boost\n"
"    patched by: builtin.dealii"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2468
msgid ""
"Here you can see that the patch is applied to ``boost`` by ``dealii``, and "
"that it lives in ``dealii``'s directory in Spack's ``builtin`` package "
"repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2473
msgid "Extensions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2475
msgid ""
"Spack's support for package extensions is documented extensively in :ref:"
"`extensions`. This section documents how to make your own extendable "
"packages and extensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2478
msgid ""
"To support extensions, a package needs to set its ``extendable`` property to "
"``True``, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2480
msgid ""
"class Python(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    extendable = True\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2487
msgid ""
"To make a package into an extension, simply add an ``extends`` call in the "
"package definition, and pass it the name of an extendable package:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2489
msgid ""
"class PyNumpy(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    extends(\"python\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2496
msgid ""
"This accomplishes a few things. Firstly, the Python package can set special "
"variables such as ``PYTHONPATH`` for all extensions when the run or build "
"environment is set up. Secondly, filesystem views can ensure that extensions "
"are put in the same prefix as their extendee. This ensures that Python in a "
"view can always locate its Python packages, even without environment "
"variables set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2501
msgid ""
"A package can only extend one other package at a time. To support packages "
"that may extend one of a list of other packages, Spack supports multiple "
"``extends`` directives as long as at most one of them is selected as a "
"dependency during concretization. For example, a lua package could extend "
"either ``lua`` or ``lua-luajit``, but not both:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2505
msgid ""
"class LuaLpeg(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"use_lua\", default=True)\n"
"    extends(\"lua\", when=\"+use_lua\")\n"
"    extends(\"lua-luajit\", when=\"~use_lua\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2514
msgid ""
"Now, a user can install, and activate, the ``lua-lpeg`` package for either "
"lua or ``lua-luajit``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2517
msgid "Adding additional constraints"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2519
msgid ""
"Some packages produce a Python extension, but require a minimum version of "
"Python to work correctly. In those cases, a ``depends_on()`` declaration "
"should be made in addition to the ``extends()`` declaration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2522
msgid ""
"class Icebin(Package):\n"
"    extends(\"python\", when=\"+python\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"python@3.12:\", when=\"+python\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2528
msgid ""
"Many packages produce Python extensions for *some* variants, but not others: "
"they should extend ``python`` only if the appropriate variant(s) are "
"selected. This may be accomplished with conditional ``extends()`` "
"declarations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2531
msgid ""
"class FooLib(Package):\n"
"    variant(\"python\", default=True, description=\"Build the Python "
"extension Module\")\n"
"    extends(\"python\", when=\"+python\")\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2539
msgid "Mixins for common metadata"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2541
msgid ""
"Spack's package repository contains a number of mixin classes that can be "
"used to simplify package definitions and to share common metadata and "
"behavior across multiple packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2543
msgid ""
"For instance, packages that depend on ``cuda`` typically need variants such "
"as ``+cuda`` and ``cuda_arch``, and conflicts to specify compatibility "
"between architectures, compilers and CUDA versions. To avoid duplicating "
"this metadata in every package that requires CUDA, Spack provides a mixin "
"class called ``CudaPackage`` that can be used to inherit this common "
"metadata and behavior."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2546
msgid ""
