#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2587
msgid "Maintainers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2589
msgid ""
"Each package in Spack may have one or more GitHub accounts for people who "
"want to be notified whenever the package is modified. The list also provides "
"contacts for people needing help with build errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2592
msgid ""
"Adding maintainers is easy. After familiarizing yourself with the "
"responsibilities of the :ref:`Package Maintainers <package-maintainers>` "
"role, you simply need to declare their GitHub accounts in the "
"``maintainers`` directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2595
msgid "maintainers(\"github_user1\", \"github_user2\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2601
msgid "Please do not add accounts without consent of the owner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2603
msgid ""
"The final list of maintainers includes accounts declared in the package's "
"base classes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2608
msgid "License Information"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2610
msgid ""
"Most of the software in Spack is open source, and most open source software "
"is released under one or more `common open source licenses <https://"
"opensource.org/licenses/>`_. Specifying the license that a package is "
"released under in a project's ``package.py`` is good practice. To specify a "
"license, find the `SPDX identifier <https://spdx.org/licenses/>`_ for a "
"project and then add it using the license directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2614
msgid "license(\"<SPDX Identifier HERE>\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2618
msgid ""
"For example, the SPDX ID for the Apache Software License, version 2.0 is "
"``Apache-2.0``, so you'd write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2620
msgid "license(\"Apache-2.0\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2624
msgid ""
"Or, for a dual-licensed package like Spack, you would use an `SPDX "
"Expression <https://spdx.github.io/spdx-spec/v2-draft/SPDX-license-"
"expressions/>`_ with both of its licenses:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2626
msgid "license(\"Apache-2.0 OR MIT\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2630
msgid ""
"Note that specifying a license without a ``when=`` clause makes it apply to "
"all versions and variants of the package, which might not actually be the "
"case. For example, a project might have switched licenses at some point or "
"have certain build configurations that include files that are licensed "
"differently. Spack itself used to be under the ``LGPL-2.1`` license, until "
"it was relicensed in version ``0.12`` in 2018."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2634
msgid ""
"You can specify when a ``license()`` directive applies using a ``when=`` "
"clause, just like other directives. For example, to specify that a specific "
"license identifier should only apply to versions up to ``0.11``, but another "
"license should apply for later versions, you could write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2637
msgid ""
"license(\"LGPL-2.1\", when=\"@:0.11\")\n"
"license(\"Apache-2.0 OR MIT\", when=\"@0.12:\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2642
msgid ""
"Note that unlike for most other directives, the ``when=`` constraints in the "
"``license()`` directive can't intersect. Spack needs to be able to resolve "
"exactly one license identifier expression for any given version. To specify "
"*multiple* licenses, use SPDX expressions and operators as above. The "
"operators you probably care most about are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2647
msgid "``OR``: user chooses one license to adhere to; and"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2648
msgid "``AND``: user has to adhere to all the licenses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2650
msgid ""
"You may also care about `license exceptions <https://spdx.org/licenses/"
"exceptions-index.html>`_ that use the ``WITH`` operator, e.g. ``Apache-2.0 "
"WITH LLVM-exception``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2652
msgid ""
"Many of the licenses that are currently in the spack repositories have been "
"automatically determined. While this is great for bulk adding license "
"information and is most likely correct, there are sometimes edge cases that "
"require manual intervention. To determine which licenses are validated and "
"which are not, there is the ``checked_by`` parameter in the license "
"directive:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2656
msgid ""
"license(\"<license>\", when=\"<when>\", checked_by=\"<github username>\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2660
msgid ""
"When you have validated a package license, either when doing so explicitly "
"or as part of packaging a new package, please set the ``checked_by`` "
"parameter to your Github username to signal that the license has been "
"manually verified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2665
msgid "Proprietary software"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2667
msgid ""
"In order to install proprietary software, Spack needs to know a few more "
"details about a package. The following class attributes should be defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2671
msgid "``license_required``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2673
msgid ""
"Boolean. If set to ``True``, this software requires a license. If set to "
"``False``, all of the following attributes will be ignored. Defaults to "
"``False``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2679
msgid "``license_comment``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2681
msgid ""
"String. Contains the symbol used by the license manager to denote a comment. "
"Defaults to ``#``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2686
msgid "``license_files``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2688
msgid ""
"List of strings. These are files that the software searches for when looking "
"for a license. All file paths must be relative to the installation "
"directory. More complex packages like Intel may require multiple licenses "
"for individual components. Defaults to the empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2695
msgid "``license_vars``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2697
msgid ""
"List of strings. Environment variables that can be set to tell the software "
"where to look for a license if it is not in the usual location. Defaults to "
"the empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2702
msgid "``license_url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2704
msgid ""
"String. A URL pointing to license setup instructions for the software. "
"Defaults to the empty string."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2708
msgid "For example, let's take a look at the Arm Forge package."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2710
msgid ""
"# Licensing\n"
"license_required = True\n"
"license_comment = \"#\"\n"
"license_files = [\"licences/Licence\"]\n"
"license_vars = [\n"
"    \"ALLINEA_LICENSE_DIR\",\n"
"    \"ALLINEA_LICENCE_DIR\",\n"
"    \"ALLINEA_LICENSE_FILE\",\n"
"    \"ALLINEA_LICENCE_FILE\",\n"
"]\n"
"license_url = \"https://developer.arm.com/documentation/101169/latest/Use-"
"Arm-Licence-Server\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2724
msgid ""
"Arm Forge requires a license. Its license manager uses the ``#`` symbol to "
"denote a comment. It expects the license file to be named ``License`` and to "
"be located in a ``licenses`` directory in the installation prefix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2728
msgid ""
"If you would like the installation file to be located elsewhere, simply set "
"``ALLINEA_LICENSE_DIR`` or one of the other license variables after "
"installation. For further instructions on installation and licensing, see "
"the URL provided."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2731
msgid ""
"If your package requires the license to install, you can reference the "
"location of this global license using ``self.global_license_file``. After "
"installation, symlinks for all of the files given in ``license_files`` will "
"be created, pointing to this global license. If you install a different "
"version or variant of the package, Spack will automatically detect and reuse "
"the already existing global license."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2735
msgid ""
"If the software you are trying to package doesn't rely on license files, "
"Spack will print a warning message, letting the user know that they need to "
"set an environment variable or pointing them to installation documentation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2739
msgid "Grouping directives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2741
msgid ""
"We have seen various directives such as ``depends_on``, ``conflicts``, and "
"``requires``. Very often, these directives share a common argument, which "
"you becomes repetitive and verbose to write."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2747
msgid "Grouping with ``when()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2749
msgid ""
"Spack provides a context manager called ``when()`` that allows you to group "
"directives by a common constraint or condition."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2751
msgid ""
"class Gcc(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    with when(\"+nvptx\"):\n"
"        depends_on(\"cuda\")\n"
"        conflicts(\"@:6\", msg=\"NVPTX only supported in gcc 7 and above\")\n"
"        conflicts(\"languages=ada\")\n"
"        conflicts(\"languages=brig\")\n"
"        conflicts(\"languages=go\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2762
msgid "The snippet above is equivalent to the more verbose:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2764
msgid ""
"class Gcc(AutotoolsPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"cuda\", when=\"+nvptx\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"@:6\", when=\"+nvptx\", msg=\"NVPTX only supported in gcc 7 "
"and above\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"languages=ada\", when=\"+nvptx\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"languages=brig\", when=\"+nvptx\")\n"
"    conflicts(\"languages=go\", when=\"+nvptx\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2774
msgid ""
"Constraints from the ``when`` block are composable with ``when`` arguments "
"in directives inside the block. For instance,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2777
msgid ""
"with when(\"+elpa\"):\n"
"    depends_on(\"elpa+openmp\", when=\"+openmp\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2782
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2830
msgid "is equivalent to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2784
msgid "depends_on(\"elpa+openmp\", when=\"+openmp+elpa\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2788
msgid ""
"Constraints from nested context managers are also combined together, but "
"they are rarely needed, and are not recommended."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2793
msgid "Grouping with ``default_args()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2795
msgid ""
"More generally, if directives have a common set of default arguments, you "
"can group them together in a ``with default_args()`` block:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2797
msgid ""
"class PyExample(PythonPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    with default_args(type=(\"build\", \"run\")):\n"
"        depends_on(\"py-foo\")\n"
"        depends_on(\"py-foo@2:\", when=\"@2:\")\n"
"        depends_on(\"py-bar\")\n"
"        depends_on(\"py-bz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2807
msgid "The above is short for:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2809
msgid ""
"class PyExample(PythonPackage):\n"
"\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-foo\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-foo@2:\", when=\"@2:\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-bar\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))\n"
"    depends_on(\"py-bz\", type=(\"build\", \"run\"))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2820
msgid ""
"The ``with when()`` context manager is composable, while ``with "
"default_args()`` merely overrides the default. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2823
msgid ""
"with default_args(when=\"+feature\"):\n"
"    depends_on(\"foo\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"bar\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"baz\", when=\"+baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2832
msgid ""
"depends_on(\"foo\", when=\"+feature\")\n"
"depends_on(\"bar\", when=\"+feature\")\n"
"depends_on(\"baz\", when=\"+baz\")  # Note: not when=\"+feature+baz\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2841
msgid "``home``, ``command``, ``headers``, and ``libs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2843
msgid ""
"Often a package will need to provide attributes for dependents to query "
"various details about what it provides. While any number of custom defined "
"attributes can be implemented by a package, the four specific attributes "
"described below are always available on every package with default "
"implementations and the ability to customize with alternate implementations "
"in the case of virtual packages provided:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2847
msgid "Attribute"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2847
msgid "Purpose"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2847
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2884
#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:3086
msgid "Default"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2849
msgid "``home``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2849
msgid "The installation path for the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2849
msgid "``spec.prefix``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2850
msgid "``command``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2850
msgid "An executable command for the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2850
msgid "``spec.name`` found in"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2852
msgid "``.home.bin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2853
msgid "``headers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2853
msgid "A list of headers provided by the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2853
msgid "All headers searched"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2855
msgid "recursively in ``.home.include``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2857
msgid "``libs``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2857
msgid "A list of libraries provided by the package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2857
msgid "``lib{spec.name}`` searched"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2859
msgid "recursively in ``.home`` starting"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2861
msgid "with ``lib``, ``lib64``, then the"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2863
msgid "rest of ``.home``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2866
msgid ""
"Each of these can be customized by implementing the relevant attribute as a "
"``@property`` in the package's class:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2868
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def libs(self):\n"
"        # The library provided by Foo is libMyFoo.so\n"
"        return find_libraries(\"libMyFoo\", root=self.home, recursive=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2879
msgid ""
"A package may also provide custom implementations of each attribute for the "
"virtual packages it provides, by implementing the ``<virtual>_<attribute>`` "
"property in its package class. The implementation used is the first one "
"found from:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2882
msgid "Specialized virtual: ``Package.<virtual>_<attribute>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2883
msgid "Generic package: ``Package.<attribute>``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2886
msgid "The use of customized attributes is demonstrated in the next example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2889
msgid "Example: Customized attributes for virtual packages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2891
msgid ""
"Consider a package ``foo`` that can optionally provide two virtual packages "
"``bar`` and ``baz``. When both are enabled, the installation tree appears as "
"follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2894
msgid ""
"include/foo.h\n"
"include/bar/bar.h\n"
"lib64/libFoo.so\n"
"lib64/libFooBar.so\n"
"baz/include/baz/baz.h\n"
"baz/lib/libFooBaz.so"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2903
msgid ""
"The install tree shows that ``foo`` provides the header ``include/foo.h`` "
"and library ``lib64/libFoo.so`` in its install prefix. The virtual package "
"``bar`` provides the header ``include/bar/bar.h`` and library ``lib64/"
"libFooBar.so``, also in ``foo``'s install prefix. The ``baz`` package, "
"however, is provided in the ``baz`` subdirectory of ``foo``'s prefix with "
"the ``include/baz/baz.h`` header and ``lib/libFooBaz.so`` library. Such a "
"package could implement the optional attributes as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2908
msgid ""
"class Foo(Package):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    variant(\"bar\", default=False, description=\"Enable the Foo "
"implementation of bar\")\n"
"    variant(\"baz\", default=False, description=\"Enable the Foo "
"implementation of baz\")\n"
"    ...\n"
"    provides(\"bar\", when=\"+bar\")\n"
"    provides(\"baz\", when=\"+baz\")\n"
"    ...\n"
"\n"
"    # Just the foo headers\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def headers(self):\n"
"        return find_headers(\"foo\", root=self.home.include, "
"recursive=False)\n"
"\n"
"    # Just the foo libraries\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def libs(self):\n"
"        return find_libraries(\"libFoo\", root=self.home, recursive=True)\n"
"\n"
"    # The header provided by the bar virtual package\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def bar_headers(self):\n"
"        return find_headers(\"bar/bar.h\", root=self.home.include, "
"recursive=False)\n"
"\n"
"    # The library provided by the bar virtual package\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def bar_libs(self):\n"
"        return find_libraries(\"libFooBar\", root=self.home, "
"recursive=True)\n"
"\n"
"    # The baz virtual package home\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def baz_home(self):\n"
"        return self.prefix.baz\n"
"\n"
"    # The header provided by the baz virtual package\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def baz_headers(self):\n"
"        return find_headers(\"baz/baz\", root=self.baz_home.include, "
"recursive=False)\n"
"\n"
"    # The library provided by the baz virtual package\n"
"    @property\n"
"    def baz_libs(self):\n"
"        return find_libraries(\"libFooBaz\", root=self.baz_home, "
"recursive=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2955
msgid "Now consider another package, ``foo-app``, depending on all three:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2957
msgid ""
"class FooApp(CMakePackage):\n"
"    ...\n"
"    depends_on(\"foo\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"bar\")\n"
"    depends_on(\"baz\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2966
msgid ""
"The resulting spec objects for its dependencies shows the result of the "
"above attribute implementations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../packaging_guide_creation.rst:2968
msgid ""
"# The core headers and libraries of the foo package\n"
"\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"]\n"
"foo@1.0/ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"].prefix\n"
"\"/opt/spack/linux-fedora35-haswell/gcc-11.3.1/foo-1.0-"
"ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6\"\n"
"\n"
"# home defaults to the package install prefix without an explicit "
"implementation\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"].home\n"
"\"/opt/spack/linux-fedora35-haswell/gcc-11.3.1/foo-1.0-"
"ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6\"\n"
"\n"
"# foo headers from the foo prefix\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"].headers\n"
"HeaderList([\n"
"    \"/opt/spack/linux-fedora35-haswell/gcc-11.3.1/foo-1.0-"
"ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6/include/foo.h\",\n"
"])\n"
"\n"
"# foo include directories from the foo prefix\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"].headers.directories\n"
"[\"/opt/spack/linux-fedora35-haswell/gcc-11.3.1/foo-1.0-"
"ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6/include\"]\n"
"\n"
"# foo libraries from the foo prefix\n"
">>> spec[\"foo\"].libs\n"
"LibraryList([\n"
"    \"/opt/spack/linux-fedora35-haswell/gcc-11.3.1/foo-1.0-"
"ca3rczp5omy7dfzoqw4p7oc2yh3u7lt6/lib64/libFoo.so\",\n"
"])\n"
"\n"
"# foo library directories from the foo prefix\n"
